<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Premier Receives Canadian Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul
Karim Kabariti met here today with Andrew Robinson, Canada's
Middle East peace coordinator, on the latest development of the
regional peace process on all tracks and the obstacles facing it.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian prime minister reiterated the kingdom's pursuit
to activate the process out of its keenness to achieve a
comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the region, Radio Jordan
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He called for collective international efforts, saying that
securing progress towards that end would help realize economic and
social development in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that endeavors should focus on solving the
refugee problems, which he said, is a "basic element" for
establishing a just peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The visit by Canada's peace coordinator to Jordan came at a
time when the stalled Middle East peace process was endangered by
Israeli "warlike" statements, Syria's troop movements in south
Lebanon and the verbal cross-attacks between Israel, Syria and
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai warned Syria Sunday
against the temptation of using military pressure to force Israel
back to the negotiating table on its terms.
</P>
<P>
"I issue this warning to Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad: 'Remember that Israel is strong and its army is ready to
carry out whatever tasks it must," said the Israeli minister.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the leading member in the Arab world, warned Monday that
Israel's warlike statements to Syria could provoke a similar
reaction in the Arab world and torpedo the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's leading daily Al Akhar said Monday that most Egyptians,
despite their 1979 peace treaty with Israel, would want a break in
ties or even a war because of the "provocative" statements made
by Israeli defense minister.
</P>
<P>
The recent eastward and southward movement of Syrian troops
from Lebanon had raised eyebrows in Jerusalem. The Israeli
government has reportedly decided to increase Israeli forces in
the Golan Heights in response to Syrian troop movements in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Israel and Syria have risen since Benjamin
Netanyahu took office in June. Netanyahu has said he does not want
to return the Golan in exchange for peace with Syria, as the
previous Israeli government had indicated it would do. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
