<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Cable-Walks Between Two Highrises in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- This evening, Canadian Jay
Cochrane successfully crossed a cable 1.5 cm thick and 196.4 m
long that stretched between two highrise buildings in Shanghai's
Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Cochrane's performance was included in the program for the
ongoing '96 Shanghai Tourist Festival.
</P>
<P>
His starting and finishing points -- the Yu'an Building and the
Bao'an Building -- are 108 m and 134 m tall, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian carried only a balancing rod during his 25-minute
walk, which is the ninth of its kind in his career, and did not
have any safety equipment on the ground below.
</P>
<P>
Cochrane, who has a master's degree in bridge engineering, said
he hoped that his cable-walk would be impressive to local
residents.
</P>
<P>
According to festival officials, Cochrane volunteered to cross
the high cable for the festival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
