<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Summary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Following is a summary of
China's diplomatic news covered today by Home News for Overseas
Service Department of Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets with Kiribati President
</P>
<P>
BEIJING--Chinese Premier Li Peng expressed his satisfaction
with the smooth growth of Sino-Kiribati friendly ties during his
meeting with visiting Kiribati President Teburoro Tito here today.
</P>
<P>
Tito's current visit will contribute to the mutual
understanding and friendship of the two countries, as well as to
expansion of bilateral cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets Belarussian Defense Minister
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today expressed the hope
that bilateral ties between China and Belarus, including the
friendly co-operation and contacts between the two armed forces,
will be further expanded.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting here with visiting Belarussian Defense
Minister Lieutenant General Leonid Semeonovich Maltsev and his
party, Li said that bilateral ties have undergone great growth
through concerted efforts of both sides.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Meets with Famous Chinese America
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met with Anne Chan
Chennault, a noted Chinese American and social activist, here
today.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li expressed his appreciations to her kind
attention and support to the cause of China's education over the
past several years.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Premier Meets with UNESCO, Malawi Guests
</P>
<P>
BEIJING-- China wishes to continue its good cooperation with
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization (UNESCO), Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said today
in a meeting with Tidjani-Serpos, the chairman of the
organization's executive board, and permanent delegate of Benin to
UNESCO.
</P>
<P>
Li said he believes that the world's prosperity and stability
cannot be realized by the turn of the century without the
participation of African countries.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier also met today with Rodwell Munyenyembe,
speaker of the National Assembly of Malawi, who was in Beijing to
attend the 96th Inter-Parliamentary Conference.
</P>
<P>
China Welcomes US Investors and Traders: Vice-Premier
</P>
<P>
BEIJING-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing today told the
Illinois State Trade Delegation, headed by Governor Jim Edgar,
that China welcomes American companies to invest in the country
and conduct trade here.
</P>
<P>
China welcomes investment in China from big businesses,
such as Motorola, as well as cooperation with small and medium-sized
enterprises, Li said in a meeting this afternoon with the group.
</P>
<P>
China's Position on Diaoyu Islands Remains Unchanged: Spokesman
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang said
at a press conference here this afternoon that the Diaoyu Islands
belong to China, and China's position on this issue remains
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Diaoyu Islands have been part of the Chinese territory
since ancient times, he said.
</P>
<P>
Reception of Dalai Lama to Affect Sino-Australian Ties: Spokesman
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Shen Guofang said
here today that the Australian Government's reception of the Dalai
Lama would have an impact on Sino-Australian relations.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference this afternoon, Shen said that China has
"stressed time after time that the Dalai Lama is more a political
figure in exile than a religious one, who engages himself in
activities aiming at splitting China."  
</P>
</TEXT>
