<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loans to Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) approved three loans or grants here today to Pakistan, Sri
Lanka and Nepal for their development projects.
</P>
<P>
The bank approved a technical assistance grant of 1.14 million
US dollars to finance a long-term strategic study on issues
relating to Pakistan's social and economic development over the
next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
The study will cover topics such as relevance of the East Asian
and Southeast Asian models to Pakistan, sound development
management, private sector-led industrialization as well as trade
liberation and export expansion.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also agreed to provide a concessional loan of 20
million US dollars to assist the Sri Lanka government in
addressing economic development problems in North-Central
province, one of the least developed provinces in the country.
</P>
<P>
At the same day, the ADB approved a 20 million dollar loan to
Nepal to develop the fourth rural water supply and sanitation
project. Nearly 600,000 people in rural Nepal will benefit from
the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
