<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Carries out Comprehensive Survey of Wild Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China has started a
nationwide comprehensive survey of the country's wild animals to
determine their population and distribution, and learn more about
their habitats.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, vice minister of forestry, said during today's
working conference on the overall survey of wild animals, that the
key to protecting wild animals is guaranteeing their growth and
development.
</P>
<P>
The five-year survey will involve 141 species of birds, 70
types of mammals and 44 kinds of reptiles in 30 provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions across the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the survey is designed to provide reliable
information that can be used to formulate an effective protection
strategy for wild animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Ministry of Forestry carried out similar surveys
in 11 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions on a trial
basis.
</P>
<P>
During China's present period of rapid economic growth, the
wasteland-reclamation efforts and development of the rural economy
have reduced the number of wildlife habitats, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there is a greater demand for the exploitation and
use of wildlife resources, he added.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said that China will create archives for the
country's wild animal resources, to guide effective protection
measures as well as domestication and exploitation strategies.
</P>
<P>
The survey, with its wide scope, is the first its kind in the
country, he said.
</P>
<P>
China now has 17,000 people working in the fields of wild
animal resource protection and research, and the country has
opened 25 wildlife protection organizations in its provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry has invested in 71 national nature
preserves and 503 local preserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
