<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong: Big Player In Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has become the
single largest outward investor among Asian developing economies,
according to the 1996 issue of the World Investment Report, which
says the outflows of Foreign Direct Investment (FDI) from the
region amounted to 25 billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
A good part of the outflows goes into China, says the report
released today in Geneva by the United Nations Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
The inflows of FDI into Hong Kong, 2.1 billion US dollars in
1995, fall far short of the outflows.
</P>
<P>
"It does not imply a loss of confidence in Hong Kong," said
Professor Edward K.Y. Chen, President of Lingnan College at a news
conference here today, who gave a general introduction to the
annual report, the fifth published by UNCTAD since 1992.
</P>
<P>
In his view, the figures simply reflect normal commercial
activities to rationalize production and accumulate wealth. Hong
Kong is a funding center which draws money from other places of
the world and then pours into China, so the big outflows are not
all from Hong Kong investors, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Touching on Hong Kong after 1997, the reports says the city
should continue to be a separate customs territory and an
independent member of the World Trade Organization
(WTO). According to Chen, there is good evidence that the whole
world has confidence in Hong Kong so long as it maintains the
current economic independence as stipulated in the Basic Law, the
de facto constitution of the future Special Administrative
Region.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD plays an important role in promoting trade and
investment throughout the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
