<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Japan to Launch Research on Nuclear Reactor Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- France and Japan are to launch
a joint research on how to deal with accidents that can lead to
partial melting of the core of rapid neutron reactors.
</P>
<P>
They signed last week a five-year contract on eight experiments
between 1996 and 2000 at 200 million francs (40 million
U.S. dollars), according to the Institute of Nuclear Protection
and Safety (IPSN) of France and the Power Reactor and Fuel
Development Corporation (PNC) of Japan today.
</P>
<P>
The program, named "Cabri-Reactor Accident Test Fuel," comes as
part of a plan by France and Japan to continue developing rapid
neutron nuclear reactors as their important energy resource in the
next century, said IPSN and PNC officials.
</P>
<P>
It will focus on the study of consequences of an uncontrolled
recovery of a control rod of the reactors and on the evolution of
physical phenomena immediately after an accident of reactivity
takes place.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France is using its 1,300 megawatt Superpheonix
reactor in Creys-Malville in the eastern part of the country to
study on reduction of plutonium stocks and elimination of products
of dangerous atomic fissions.
</P>
<P>
The first French-Japanese joint experiment will be launched in
November at the IPSN installations in Cadarache, southeast of
France.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese 280-megawatt Monju reactor has been out of service
since 1994 when a fire accident caused a breakdown of the
installation. The incident aroused protests from ecologists and
is still under investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
