<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Meets Egyptian Ambassador to Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- In a sign of deepening
feud, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy today summoned
Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed Bassyouni to protest so-called
Cairo's anti-Israeli statements.
</P>
<P>
Levy told Bassiouny that Egypt should halt the recent verbal
attacks heard from Cairo, if it wanted the peace process to
advance.
</P>
<P>
Bassyouni, on his part, denied that Egypt had issued an
ultimatum to Israel, but only wanted it to take "tangible steps"
to push forward the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, Bassiouny telephoned Cabinet Secretary Danny
Naveh to explain that Cairo's statements might have been
misquoted by the press. He said it was not Egypt's policy to
attack any individual despite the difference existing between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli protest came after recent press reports quoted
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
as warning that Israel's hardline policies could lead to the
revival of Palestinian uprising and set back bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
In a newspaper interview, Moussa reportedly demanded that
Israel take quick actions in the following weeks in the following
fields: immediately pulling back its troops from the West Bank
town of Hebron; reviving the final-status talks with the
Palestinians; lifting the closure on Palestinian territories;
resuming peace talks with Syria at the point it broke off;
declaring its willingness to withdraw troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a sharper attack Monday, Egyptian Assistant Foreign
Minister Fathi el-Shazli lashed out at statements made by Israeli
leaders, including Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, on recent
tension with Syria, describing them as "banging of war drums." He
said Israeli leaders were "amateur politicians" who talked like
"dinosaurs."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Egypt staged last week the biggest military
exercise in history aimed at countering a possible
non-conventional attack by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has long demanded Israel renounce its nuclear capability
or subject it to international inspection. The nuclear issue is
one of the major obstacles blocking the improvement of relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt was the first Arab country to make peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
To push forward the peace process, Egypt, playing a leading
role in the Arab world, has been trying to form an united Arab
front against Israel after the hardline Likud government came to
power in June. The Egyptian moves caused great displeasure among
the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Despite Netanyahu's July visit to Cairo, his first trip to an
Arab country, and Levy's visit early this month, the deep
differences between Egypt and Israel seemed to have hardly been
bridged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
