<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Who Will Be Successor to Banharn? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Who could succeed Banharn
Silpa-Archa as prime minister has turned into a hottest topic in
Thailand these days after Banharn Saturday was forced to resign
within a week.
</P>
<P>
Political party leaders and top executives frequently met over
the weekend in a bid to reach consensus on a candidate for the
post amid the looming possibility that embattled Banharn might
choose to dismiss parliament for a new general election.
</P>
<P>
Currently, choosing a candidate who will satisfy all the six
coalition parties seems to be a very tough task as major
differences exist among the six coalition parties, especially
between Banharn and New Aspiration Party (NAP) leader Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
Banharn gave up his prime minister throne to exchange for
support from his coalition partners in the censure debate against
him in parliament, when Chavalit led a sudden coalition drive to
push Banharn to resign in exchange for their support minutes
before the voting on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Banharn survived the vote by 207 to 180, but he might not
forgive Chavalit. Banharn reportedly has planned to propose
Pramarn Adireksarn, founder of the Chart Thai (Thai Nation) Party
(CTP), or his son Pongpol Adireksarn, to succeed him to block
Chavalit from becoming new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
However, Chavalit, leader of the second largest ruling party
and also deputy prime minister and defense minister, was backed by
some party leaders, including Nam Thai (Thai Leadership) Party
(NTP) leader Anmuay Virawan and Palang Dharma (Virtue Force) party
leader Thaksin Shinawatra.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit currently is the most powerful candidate within the
coalition and some local newspapers said that the six coalition
parties (including some CTP members) have reached a tacit
agreement on choosing Chavalit as new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay, who is an economic expert, is
another potential candidate within the coalition, as the country
needs an economic leader to tackle the existing economic woes.
</P>
<P>
A recent small-scale informal survey among Thai leading
businessmen conducted by the newspaper Bangkok Post showed that
Anmuay topped the list.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Anmuay may have problems in controlling the coalition as
his party only have 18 seats in parliament and analysts said the
cabinet under his leadership would be highly volatile with a
little party backing.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, if the six coalition parties -- CTP, NAP, NTP,
Prachakorn Thai (Thai Citizen) Party, Muan Chon (Mass) Party and
Social Action Party -- fail to reach consensus on a candidate from
the coalition, Chatichai Choonhavan, leader of the Chart Pattana
(National Development) Party might have an opportunity to step in
as new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Banharn now is using his last trump card - dismissal of
parliament - to negotiate with his coalition partners to win
favorable arrangements in the new government for his party before
he resigns, although his coalition partners insisted that Banharn
should resign before they elect a new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
At present, with Banharn's strong opposition to Chavalit and
insistence of choosing a successor from the CTP, the situation
remains complicated. The selection of a new prime minister might
resort to a parliamentary election, so it is quite possible for a
black horse to emerge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
