<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Invited to Rome Food Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is one of several
African countries to participate in a crucial meeting in Rome to
discuss a draft plan of action to achieve universal food security
in less than 15 years, Zimbabwe National News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is also expected to finalize a draft declaration
on food security to be signed by world leaders who will attend
the world food Summit in Rome from November 13 to 17.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, because of its strategic importance in ensuring food
security in the 12-member Southern African Development Community,
has accepted the invitation from the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) to send a high-powered delegation
to the summit.
</P>
<P>
The draft plan commits the leaders to new initiatives to place
food security at the top of policy priorities and eliminate all
obstacles frustrating increased food output.
</P>
<P>
The draft declaration commits leaders to giving greater
priority to the development of rural areas to reverse migration
to urban areas, and put in place measures to ensure adequate food
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan of action, leaders will be asked to enact
macro-economic and agricultural policies that permit food and
agricultural producers to earn a fair return on labor.
</P>
<P>
The plan of action also lists other programs to be initiated
by governments to promote agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
