<HEADLINE> Israel to Import Jordanian Farm Produce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Agricultural Marketing
Corporation (AMC) of Jordan Monday announced that the Israeli
government agreed to import several kinds of fresh Jordanian
fruits and vegetables from now until the end of December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian exports to Israel will be exempted from customs
in implementation of the agreements signed between the two
countries, the English daily Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The AMC called on Jordanian farmers to enter the Israeli
market and export agricultural products of international
standards.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said AMC's board of directors agreed to import
mango, avocado and kiwi from Israel as of October 1 until the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
They said the Israeli authorities agreed that the Jordanian
importers of Israeli commodities could in turn export Jordanian
agricultural produce to the Israeli market.
</P>
<P>
They added that the agricultural products allowed to enter the
Israeli market are tomato, cucumber, hot pepper, lettuce,
eggplants, squash, beans, apples, grapes and various kinds of
melons.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Israel opened door wider for Jordanian exports to
the Palestinian self-rule areas by increasing the quotas on the
list of goods the Palestinians are allowed to import from Jordan,
without being subject to Israeli standards.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials accused earlier this year the Israeli
government of hindering the implementation of Jordanian-Israeli
and Jordanian-Palestinian trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government repeatedly asked its Israeli
counterpart to take concrete measures to boost trade exchange
between the two sides and between Jordan and the West Bank, in
order to make the ordinary Jordanians feel the "peace dividends."
</P>
<P>
Figures available show that Jordan witnessed a great trade
deficit with Israel last year, with 825,000 U.S. dollars of
imports and 85,500 dollars of exports.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel signed a peace agreement in October 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
