<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asthma To Rise As Result of Global Warming, Say </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The world's asthmatic
population would rise as global warming created ideal breeding
conditions for dust mites, mould and cockroaches and caused dogs
and cats to moult and salivate more, a conference heard today.
</P>
<P>
Higher temperatures would also lead to more use of air
conditioning and insulation, decreasing the turnover of indoor air
and allowing asthma allergens to multiply, Macquarie University
scientists Prof. Peter Curson and Dr. Paul Beggs told the Climate
Change and Human Health Conference here.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 million people, they said, around the world
already suffered from asthma, including two million Australians.
Almost one million school days were lost each year in Australia
because of the chronic airways disorder which was the most
important reason for hospitalization of young children.
</P>
<P>
"Climate change will have profound effects on asthma not only
by directly influencing the distribution, life cycle and
prevalence of a wide range of allergens and irritants but also by
indirectly influencing human behavior," the scientists told the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The most common asthma triggers were house dust mites,
cockroaches, mould and hair and saliva from domestic pets. Dust
mites and cockroaches both bred best where the temperature was
over 20 degrees Celsius while moulds did well in dark, humid and
poorly ventilated conditions.
</P>
<P>
Australia had the highest rate of pet ownership in the world
with the number of domestic pets likely to grow with the human
population. Many of these pets spend considerable time inside
homes in close contact with their owners.
</P>
<P>
"Warmer temperatures and higher humidity may also influence the
moulting pattern of pets like cats and may also have an impact on
saliva production," the scientists pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Excludes 20 Indicted Rwandans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) announced today it was
excluding from refugee statues 20 Rwandans in connection with the
1994 genocide in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here today, the UNHCR also urged
governments to take the same measure if these Rwandans, indicted
by the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR), seek
asylum.
</P>
<P>
"The 20 Rwandans are believed to be among those behind the
execution and planning of the genocide in which more than 500,000
Rwandans were killed," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Some of these Rwandans are in the custody of the tribunal,
including three who were arraigned in the Tanzanian town of
Arusha in June. The others are believed to be in Europe and
Africa," it added.
</P>
<P>
The exclusions were first announced by UNHCR on the basis of
the ICTR indictments since more than two million Rwandan refugees
flooded into neighboring Zaire, Tanzania and Burundi following
the three-month civil war and genocide in Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council resolution which established the
ICTR requires the cooperation of inter-governmental and
non-governmental organizations and countries to take measures to
bring to justice persons responsible for the genocide and
flagrant violations of international humanitarian law in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees, to
which 131 states are currently party, sets out the criteria for
recognition of refugees and standards for their treatment.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for the exclusion of "any person with respect
to whom there are serious reasons for considering that he has
committed a crime against peace, a war crime, or a crime against
humanity."
</P>
<P>
A similar exclusion provision is found in the 1969 Refugee
Convention of the Organization of the African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
UNHCR believed that the indictments by the tribunal constitute
sufficient grounds for exclusion from refugee status in
accordance with its own mandate and the OAU convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
