<HEADLINE> Quake Jolts Palu, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 4.0
on the open-ended Richter scale jolted the central Sulawesi
capital of Palu Monday night, causing thousands of people to flee
their homes, Antara News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Palu Meteorological and Geophysical Office said the quake's
epicenter was traced at Tomini Bay, some 66 kilometers north of
Palu.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate report of casualties and material
damages.
</P>
<P>
Central Sulawesi was last hit by an earthquake measuring 4.8 on
the Richter scale on September 5 when a total of 209 houses and
four school buildings in Donggala district were damaged.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, a powerful quake measuring 7.0 on the
open-ended Richter scale jolted the districts of Buol, Toli-Toli
and Donggala, claiming nine lives and devastating thousands of
houses and public facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
