<HEADLINE> Palestinian Demonstrators Clash With Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers wounded
and arrested a number of Palestinian demonstrators in clashes
in the West Bank town of Hebron today.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service
based in East Jerusalem, the Palestinians this morning marched
from Al-Sinyeh Mosque in Hebron's old city to the closed
vegetable market, which has been shut down since the 1994 Hebron
massacre.
</P>
<P>
A popular rally was held there. The participants demanded the
reopening of the market in accordance with the Oslo 2 agreement,
calling for a halt to the Jewish settlement expansion and for
implementation of Israeli troop redeployment from Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The rally was attended by Hanan Ashrawi, member of the
Palestinian Council and Palestinian Authority Minister of Higher
education, Abdul Jaward Saleh, member of the Palestinian Council,
Mustafa Natshe, Mayor of Hebron, and a number of noted
Palestinian figures.
</P>
<P>
The rally turned into a demonstration when Israeli soldiers
came to intervene. Physical clashes happened between the two
sides. Soldiers indiscriminately beat the demonstrators, who threw
stones at them in response.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers threatened to beat Ashrawi and Natshe but were
blocked by demonstrators. Three Palestinians were wounded and an
ABC photographer was also attacked. A total of seven Palestinians
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli military authorities declared Hebron to be a
closed military zone, but clashes are still continuing in
various parts of the West Bank city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
