<HEADLINE> Malaysian Navy to Set up Another Large Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Malaysian Navy
(RMN) will set up its second largest base at a 144-hectare site at
Teluk Sepangar in Sabah State, Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar
said today.
</P>
<P>
The RMN base will be constructed in stages and the first phase
will involve a cost of 60 to 100 million ringgit (about 24 to 40
million US dollars), he was quoted by Malaysia's official news
agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
But he did not disclose when the construction of the naval base
in Teluk Sepangar will commence.
</P>
<P>
The largest RMN base is situated in Lumut, Perak State.
</P>
<P>
Teluk Sepangar was selected for setting up the second largest
RMN base because it is situated in a strategic area besides many
other natural advantages and its deep waters, according to a
defense ministry statement.
</P>
<P>
When the proposed base is completed, the RMN would continue to
maintain its presence in Labuan, a Federal Territory close to
Sabah, but at a smaller scale, the statement said, adding the RMN
base in Labuan would be used as a logistics depot.  
</P>
</TEXT>
