<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish tourism association TURSAB held the 10th
annual awards ceremony in Istanbul, during which 104 successful
agencies received prizes, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Minister of Tourism Bahattin Yucel said at the
ceremony held Monday that "Turkey is the fastest developing
country in tourism in the world," adding that the income from
tourism had increased to five billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Yucel said that Turkey has one million hotel rooms at present,
and some 20 million tourists visit the country annually.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's National Society for Consumer Protection
(NSCP) has confirmed that certain families in the country will
spend additional 23 dinars (about 32.2 U.S. dollars) per month due
to extra expenses incurred by the recent price hikes of basic
commodities.
</P>
<P>
A recent study by the NSCP regarding extra expenses resulting
from price increases, including bread price hikes, demonstrated
that the additional expenses various families have to be burdened
averages 32.2 U.S. dollars, according to today's Jordan Times, the
kingdom's sole English daily.
</P>
<P>
NSCP President Homhammad Obeidat said that the average income
of the surveyed families, with an average of seven members each,
was 175 dinars (about 225 dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that some families who earn less than 175 dinars have
been badly affected and that such families pay up to 10 percent
of their income to cover the rise of bread price.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Businessmen Association in Egypt's port city
Alexandria opened a new project to develop small and handicraft
establishment, local Arabic newspaper Al Ahram reported today.
</P>
<P>
The loan offered amounted to four million U.S. dollars in favor of
small industrial projects in Kafr Al-Sheikh governorate.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Economy and International
goooperation Nawal al-Tatawi has affirmed that a regional economic
conference would be a good opportunity for reviewing Egypt's role
and responsibility in upholding Middle East peace process and
opportunities for investment, local Arabic newspaper al-Ahram said
today.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Middle East and North African Economic Summit
Scheduled in November in Cairo was considered to be a unique
opportunity for consolidating economic ties inside the region and
with the world economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
