<HEADLINE> Ramos Urges Peace Pact Opponents Not to Go Beyond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos today warned those who are still against the peace efforts
in Mindanao not to go beyond the limits of the law.
</P>
<P>
"We have every right to express our disagreement, but let us
not be disagreeable," Ramos told a multisectoral assembly at
Kidapawan, North Cotabato province in southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government and the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF) signed a peace agreement on September 2 to end a
24-year-old war in Mindanao. Part of the peace agreement is the
establishment of a zone of peace and development and the Southern
Philippines Council for Peace and Development.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace agreement raised widespread opposition from
the Christian majority in Mindanao and other rebel groups such as
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the government and MILF are preparing to
hold peace talks, but the armed vigilante groups in Mindanao still
pose threat to the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ramos has toured the region several times, but every time he
went there he heard a lot of opposition to the peace efforts. Some
local people even threw rotten tomatoes at the president to voice
their anger at the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has recognized the lawful right of
the people to express their opposition, but "I also admonish them
not to go beyond the limits of the law," the president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
