<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Zaire Exchange Fire Overnight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda today accused Zairean
troops of firing at its forces in the border town of Bukavu at
first, resulting in the exchange of eight hours of heavy gunfire
between the two sides overnight.
</P>
<P>
A report from Kigali quoted Emmanuel Ndahiro, Adviser to
Rwandan Vice-President and Defense Minister Paul Kagame as
saying that Zairean forces in Bukavu opened fire first, using
anti-aircraft guns and 75 mm recoiless rifles.
</P>
<P>
It was the second night of fighting between the two sides.
Observers here say they fought for the reason of more then one
million Rwandan refugees present in the eastern part of Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda accuses Zaire of backing its Hutu rebels to cross in to
mount raids inside the country while Zaire accuses Rwanda of
helping Tutsis from Burundi infiltrate into eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
``There was more fighting last night. We are checking for
casualties. The truth is that the zaireans fired first. We
opened fire in response,'' Ndahiro said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. agencies are evacuating non-essential
expatriate staff from Bukavu because of the deteriorating
situation there.
</P>
<P>
``There is a plan to evacuate non-essential expatriate staff
from Bukavu. We have sent recommendations to headquarters and we
are awaiting a response,'' Fernando Del Mundo, spokesman for the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
