<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adventure Team Drifts Up Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A team of adventurers are
retracing a drift along China's longest river which ended
tragically ten years ago when five people were killed.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 team is composed of more than ten adventurers,
scientists and reporters. They have left Chengdu, capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province, on their high-risk drift up
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The journey is marking the 10th anniversary of the first
drifting adventure on the river in 1986, when five members of an
adventure team were killed after scoring many scientific
achievements during their perilous drift.
</P>
<P>
To memorize the glorious event and encourage more young people
to take part in scientific adventures, relevant departments of the
province organized the current team to re-visit the origin and
upper reaches of the Yangtze river, which is the third longest in
the world.
</P>
<P>
The adventure will cover more than 8,000 kilometers, and mainly
focus on the relationship between mankind and the ecological
environment. It is hoped the journey will inspire people to gain
more understanding of the river and the western part of China in
particular.
</P>
<P>
Adventure study of the ecological environment is becoming a
popular pastime in China, but it is very risky due to geographic
dangers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
