<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Current Account Deficit Hits Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current account
deficit skyrocketed to 15.24 billion U.S. dollars in the first
eight months of this year, more than doubling the 7.33 billion
dollars registered for the same period last year, the Bank of
Korea said today.
</P>
<P>
The deficit for the eight-month period exceeded the projection
of 15 billion dollars revised by the government for the whole
year, the bank noted.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the actual deficit for the entire year is now
estimated to break through the 20-billion-dollar mark,
representing 5 percent of the estimated gross national product for
the year against the optimum 3-percent level.
</P>
<P>
In August alone, the country's current account deficit stood at
3.49 billion dollars, a record monthly high this year.
</P>
<P>
Such a huge deficit results from rapid increase in imports,
extravagant spending at home and abroad, and a slash in prices
of such major export items as semiconductors, a bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The current account comprises trade in goods and services as
well as investment income and government payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
