<HEADLINE> Philippines Concerned About Trade Deficit, Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank's
number one concern is now the country's growing trade deficit
along with high inflation, a senior bank official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a monetary conference, central bank Governor
Gabriel Singson said that the monetary authorities is no longer
worried about the country's foreign exchange rate, but about
external trade balance and price stability.
</P>
<P>
"The trade deficit is a concern. We don't deny it," Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
For the first half of this year, the Philippines' foreign trade
deficit amounted to 6 billion US dollars, representing an increase
of 40 percent from last year. It widened further to 7.1 billion
dollars in July this year.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the International Monetary Fund is urging the
Philippine government to take measures to curb the nation's
widening trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The nation's inflation also takes a great part of the bank's
concern, though it dropped to 7.9 percent last month from a peak
of 11.3 percent in September 1995, Singson said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
