<HEADLINE> Macao People Pin High Hopes on Newly-Elected LA Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- People from all walks of life
in Macao are placing high hopes on the newly-elected members of
Macao's Legislative Assembly (LA), including the eight directly
elected and eight indirectly elected.
</P>
<P>
The Macao governor, officials of the Xinhua News Agency Macao
Branch and celebrities in Macao have expressed hopes that the LA
members would help contribute to the prosperity and stability of
Macao.
</P>
<P>
While praising Sunday's election as "full of democratic
dialogues", Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira said in a written
speech that the newly-elected members of the LA are expected to
work hard for the happiness of Macao residents and for a
successful transition of Macao.
</P>
<P>
"I also hope that they will contribute to the prosperity and
stability of Macao in the future," said the governor.
</P>
<P>
Zong Guangyao, deputy-director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao
Branch, told reporters that it is his hope that the new members of
the LA would work hard for a stable transition and a smooth
handover of power in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"I congratulate them on their success," he said. "I hope they
would exercise their duty for a stable transition of Macao before
1999 and a smooth handover of power on December 20, 1999. I also
hope they would protect the interests of Macao residents."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Anabela Sales Ritchie, president of the LA, noted
that the new LA will be of great significance to the transitional
period of Macao. She expects the new members to work hard for
Macao's future and fulfill their duty in making laws and in
supervising the government work.
</P>
<P>
The election of the LA, which has 23 seats including seven
appointed by the governor, has attracted much attention and
aroused great enthusiasm of Macao people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
