<HEADLINE> FIFA Chief Expresses His World Cup Worry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Secretary general Joseph
S. Blatter of FIFA, world soccer governing body, Tuesday in Zurich
expressed his personal worry to get the South Korean and Japanese
organizers of the World Cup 2002 together.
</P>
<P>
In an interview given to the Neue Zurcher Zeitung after the
voters of the city of Zurich had approved a land-lease agreement
allowing FIFA to expand its headquarters, Blatter said the
approving votes showed that "FIFA is very popular in Zurich."
</P>
<P>
But It might be less popular on Seoul and Tokyo, he hinted.
</P>
<P>
"Representatives from the two national federations were here
last week, on separate visits. It is very difficult to get the two
parties together. The first meeting is scheduled for November
6. They have diametrically opposing ideas about co-hosting the
World Cup," a report quoted Blatter as saying.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said that the two parties had taken part in informal
talks, but that the meeting was quickly over.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, that it was "out of the question" that FIFA
would go back on its decision and award the tournament to a third
country.
</P>
<P>
The secretary general also said that it was highly unlikely
that one of the two nations would withdraw.  
</P>
</TEXT>
