<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Jacques Barrot, French Minister of Labor and Social Affairs,
on Monday presented a draft law on the financing of social
security system, which is designed to cut its deficit from 47.5
billion francs (9.5 billion U.S. dollars) to 30 billion francs (6
billion U.S. dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
A 4.5 billion franc (900 million U.S. dollars) extra money,
which is expected to come from the 17 percent rise of taxes on
tobacco and alcohol products next year, will be used to finance
social security system.
</P>
<P>
-- By choosing moderate socialists instead of radical
nationalists in the legislative election on Sunday, the Greeks
scored a victory for Europe. The victorious socialist leader,
Prime Minister Costas Simitis said that diplomacy will be the only
response to "Turkish brutality," turning down a call for military
confrontation with Ankara by some radical nationalists.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Le Figaro, Iraqi Vice Prime Minister
Tarik Aziz said that the United States and Iran are two real
threats to the Gulf region. Describing the U.S. policy towards
Iraq in the past five years as a failure, Aziz said that the
confrontation between Baghdad and Washington has not ended. He
praised France for "listening to" and "speaking with" Iraq.
</P>
<P>
-- To fight against the problem of violence among young people
in France, President of the Superior Audio-video Council Herve
Bourges said on Monday that the government will restrict the
airing of films with particular violent scenes on television in
peak hours. The measures also include putting visible codes on
the screen to signify the degree of violence of the films, which
are classified into five categories.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the parents in France think that television
is responsible for the aggressiveness of their children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
