<HEADLINE> China's Road-building Plans Will Need Huge Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China is to race ahead with a
major road-building program, using foreign funds to meet the
construction costs.
</P>
<P>
The country will build 6,500 kilometers of new expressway roads
in the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are being welcomed to participate in the
building and management of the projects in various ways, said
Huang Zhendong, minister of communications.
</P>
<P>
The Nanjing-Shanghai expressway Stock Company, in east China's
Jiangsu Province, has applied to issue shares overseas to raise
funds to build projects along the Nanjing-Shanghai Expressway,
which runs through five major cities in Jiangsu, and new
expressways within its boundary.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Huaqiang, director of the provincial
communications department, Jiangsu will absorb huge sums of
overseas investment in the building of five inner-province
expressways on the northern bank of the Yangtze River between 1996
and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China's Liaoning Province plans to sell part of the
shares for building the Shenyang-Dalian Expressway, the first of
its kind in China, to raise funds for technological transformation
in existing industrial firms, said Wen Shizhen, governor of
Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
Hebei Province is building an expressway which is part of the
Beijing-Shenzhen trunk road with a loan of 240 million US dollars
from the World Bank, and a 400-km-long expressway between
Qinhuangdao and Beijing with a 200 million US dollar loan from the
Asian Development Bank.  
</P>
</TEXT>
