<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fast Road Link Boosts Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A new expressway linking
Shanghai with Nanjing is expected to boost the economy along the
route by 25 percent, market analysts estimated.
</P>
<P>
The road, which shortens travel hour between the two major
Chinese cities to three hours from previous nine hours, traverses
some of China's richest cities including Suzhou, Wuxi, Changzhou
and Zhenjiang in the Yangtze River Delta.
</P>
<P>
Existing expressways and others still under construction are
designed to form a network in the region, and also connect with
high-grade national roads, leading as far north as Beijing,
northernmost Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The route is only part of a national express highway network
with a total length of more than 3,000 kilometers. Before 1990,
the country only had 522 kilometers of express highway.
</P>
<P>
According to plans, about ten express highways will open to
traffic in the coming two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
