<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 07:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Thwarts Israeli Penetration in Lebanon (by Shao Jie) (I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Guerrillas of the Lebanese
pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, announced today that they
thwarted an infiltrating attempt by Israeli troops in an
Israeli-occupied border strip at midnight.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued this morning, the Hezbollah guerrillas
said that an Israeli force went down stealthly its position on the
hill of Souida and advanced towards the guerrilla base of Habboush
at Iglim Al-Toffah, a ridge opposite the so-called "security zone."
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas blocked the Israeli troops by showering them hails
of bullets from various weapons, and the fighting lasted until
dawn, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's artillery shelled sporadically over the night and
earlier in the morning around Iglim Al-Toffah, which is oftened
used by guerrillas as a springboard for launching attacks at the
Israeli occupation forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The bombardments were accompanied by reconnaissance flights of
Israeli helicopters over the area.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah guerrillas also announced that they carried out an
attack at a position of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
militia at Tomat Niha in the buffer zone Monday, "killing and
wounding a number of militiamen."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli client militia confirmed that eight mortar shells
were fired by the guerrillas at its position, but denied any
casualties.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the night clash, the tensions in south
Lebanon, which had shrouded the area since last Thursday, was
considerably eased Monday following contacts by Washington
with parties concerned, according to diplomatic sources in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berri, following his meeting with
President Elias Hrawi Monday, noted that the tension in south
Lebanon was only created by the Jewish state in order "to press
for financial and military aid from the United States."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Lebanese army was continuing sending
more reinforcements to the southern part of Beqaa Valley in
eastern Lebanon and strengthening positions in the area in
preparation for possible Israeli attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 07:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Thwarts Israeli Penetration in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Security sources said that the Lebanese army sent hundreds of
commandos Monday to Western Beqaa to reinforce the army troops
already there.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese army sent a reinforcement of some 2,000 troops
backed by tanks and armored personnel carriers to the area on the
weekend, a move carried out "by coordination" with Syria's
35,000-strong forces in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Syria has redeployed about one third of its troops in Lebanon
from Beirut and its suburbs to the range of mountains on the
Lebanese-Syrian border in the past few weeks in view of
repeated Israeli threats of strike in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a five-nation committee monitoring
a cease-fire between Lebanon and Israel is to resume its meeting
in a south Lebanese border town this morning to discuss
complaints lodged by Lebanon and the Jewish state against each
other.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called by Lebanon to discuss two complaints it
filed to the committee, accusing Israel of violating the
cease-fire by shelling southern Lebanon's villages Thursday and
deporting two Lebanese families from a border strip occupied by
the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel also complained to the committee that guerrillas of
Lebanon's pro-Iranian Hezobllah fired on its forces from three
civilian-inhabited villages in the area that day.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour session at Naqura Sunday, the cease-fire
monitoring committee grouping the United States, France, Israel,
Lebanon and Syria adjourned the meeting because of the Jewish holy
day of Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth meeting of the cease-fire monitoring
committee, but the first at Lebanon's request. The previous
three meetings were called by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up under a cease-fire understanding
brokered by the United States between Lebanon and Israel, which
put an end to a 17-day Israeli blitz against Hezbollah,
and which is aimed at protecting civilians on both sides from
any military activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
