<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Make Missile Defense Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher and his Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov
announced a defense agreement on Monday clarifying the legality of
certain American weapons used to defend against slower-flying
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
The accord was reached during their 3 1/2-hour meeting at a New
York hotel. Christopher hailed it as a "milestone."
</P>
<P>
"This important progress assures that we can effectively defend
against theater ballistic missiles while ensuring the integrity of
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty," Christopher said Monday after
meeting with Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the accord will have a "significant, positive
effect" on debate in the Russian Duma, the national legislature,
on ratifying the START II nuclear arms reduction treaty which the
U.S. Congress has already ratified.
</P>
<P>
Lynn Davis, a State Department official, told reporters later
that Christopher and Primakov had confirmed a detailed agreement
worked out in June and that they expect the documents to be
formally signed by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
In practical terms, Ms. Davis said, the accord clarifies the
legality of a new-generation anti-missile system under development
by the Pentagon called the Theater High Altitude Area Defense
system, which is designed to shoot down incoming ballistic
missiles at far greater ranges than the Patriot is capable of.
</P>
<P>
The deal applies to those anti-missile missiles that fly at
speeds no greater than 3 kilometers per second. Discussions on
faster-flying missiles will be the next step.
</P>
<P>
Washington and Moscow have argued for years over identifying
those anti-missile defensive systems, such as the U.S. Army's
Patriot air defense system, that are allowed under the 1972 ABM
Treaty and those capable of shooting down long-range missiles,
which are expressly limited under the treaty.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two senior diplomats also discussed
Russia's relations with NATO, the Bosnian elections and the
situation in Iraq, but reached no new agreements on NATO's
expansion plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Education Ministry Lacks Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The annual budgetary
allocation to the Ministry of Education is still inadequate to
build schools, Zimbabwean Education Minister Edmund Garwe said
yesterday in Bulawayo, the country's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
Garwe said the 460 million U.S. Dollars allocated to the
ministry this year would not satisfy the needs of the
ever-existing local education system.
</P>
<P>
He said of the 460 million Dollars for 1996/97, 92 percent
went to salaries of more than 100,000 teachers and other staff.
</P>
<P>
"Four percent goes to administration and the remainder is for
development but it is just too little to build new schools. From
this money we have allocated 1.8 million U.S. Dollars to assist
advanced level schools which are mostly privately run," said
Garwe.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministry could afford to build more schools if
about 20 percent of its allocation was for development.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we urgently need to build 38 secondary schools to
cater for close to 40,000 children who cannot be accommodated on
existing schools. Bulawayo alone needs 10 secondary schools but
there is no money," said Garwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
