<HEADLINE> Xinhua international News Summary at 0800 GMT, September 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and his
Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov announced a defense agreement
on Monday clarifying the legality of certain American weapons used
to defend against slower-flying ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
The accord was reached during their 3 1/2-hour meeting at a New
York hotel. Christopher hailed it as a "milestone."
</P>
<P>
"This important progress assures that we can effectively defend
against theater ballistic missiles while ensuring the integrity of
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty," Christopher said Monday after
meeting with Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the accord will have a "significant, positive
effect" on debate in the Russian Duma, the national legislature,
on ratifying the START II nuclear arms reduction treaty which the
U.S. Congress has already ratified.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Guerrillas of the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or
Party of God, announced today that they thwarted an infiltrating
attempt by Israeli troops in an Israeli-occupied border strip at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued early today, the Hezbollah guerrillas
said that an Israeli force went down stealthly its position on the
hill of Souida and advanced towards the guerrilla base of Habboush
at Iglim Al-Toffah, a ridge opposite the so-called "security zone."
</P>
<P>
Guerrillas blocked the Israeli troops by showering them hails
of bullets from various weapons, and the fighting lasted until
dawn, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. space shuttle Atlantis undocked from
Russian space station Mir Monday, ending the five-day joint
operations and picking up woman astronaut Shannon Lucid back for
the ride home.
</P>
<P>
The two spacecraft separated slowly while flying over European
mountain region at 9:33 p.m. EDT, right on time as scheduled.
About two hours later, commander Bill Readdy will fire Atlantis'
engines to move quickly from Mir for the final time until Atlantis
returns to the Russian station next January for another docking.
</P>
<P>
The nine astronauts and cosmonauts finished final transfer
activities and verified the inventory lists of materials Sunday
night. More than one ton of water was transferred from Atlantis
to Mir, along with logistical supplies, food and scientific
hardware. 
</P>
</TEXT>
