<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM to Visit Libya, Nigeria, Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan is expected to make his second foreign trip to
Egypt, Libya and Nigeria between October 2 and 8, local newspaper
Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish sources said that the Western countries worry about
Erbakan's visit to Libya and Nigeria, both black-listed by the
West, so the visit will be seen as a sign of further
anti-Western defiance by Turkey's Islamist prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Libya is currently facing international sanctions for not
turning in two men suspected of involvement in the bombing of a
Pan Am passenger jet over Lockerbie in 1988, killing all
aboard.
</P>
<P>
Turkey also has its own problems with Libya concerning a debt
of 300 million U.S. dollars Libya owes to Turkish contracting
companies for work done in that country.
</P>
<P>
Turkish State Ministers Abdullah Gul and Namik Kemal Zeybek
visited Libya only a few weeks ago, but failed to secure any
results concerning the money owed to Turkish contractors.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan's other destination is also facing international
sanctions for the coup carried out by its current military
strong-man Sanni Abacha.
</P>
<P>
On his first visit abroad in August, Erbakan visited Iran,
Pakistan, Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister signed a multi-billion dollar
natural gas deal with Iran at a time when the United States
announced that it would try and punish companies from other
countries that invested in Iran's oil and gas industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
