<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chongqing, Bridge Between China's East, West (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The city has made strong efforts to build up a sound and
complete market system. Up to now, a large number of markets of
various kinds have been set up. These include large malls for farm
products, building materials and daily commodities, as well as for
futures, securities, labor, foreign exchange, technology and
information.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Chongqing City had 200,000 commercial
institutions, with a total staff of 500,000. Meanwhile, the city
hosts a dozen national or regional trade fairs annually.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Chongqing has become a regional commercial center,
with consumer goods sales reaching 28.1 billion yuan in 1995,
ranking the second in Yangtze River area, following Shanghai, and
the sixth in the country.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the city has also made efforts to strengthen
its financial and banking capability through developing its
banking industry.
</P>
<P>
So far, the city has over 3,000 banking institutions, including
nine engaged in international business. The Chongqing Branch of
Bank of China has become the largest foreign exchange market in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The development of Chongqing has brought positive effects to
neighboring areas. One of the city's industrial pillars, the
automotive industry, is an example. The industry realized 20
billion yuan in sales in 1995, while 50 percent of automobile
parts and accessories were supplied by enterprises in neighboring
areas.
</P>
<P>
In the Three Gorges Dam Area, except Chongqing itself, nearly
200 companies are making parts and fittings for the city's
manufacturers of automobiles and motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese economists have predicted that in the coming 15
years, Chongqing will become one of the most active economic areas
in the country, and will function as a bridge between the
developed eastern region and underdeveloped western part of
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6 Killed in Taliban's Rocket Attack on Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban Militia
today fired dozens of rockets into Kabul, killing at least six
people and injuring 22 others, said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The report said that several houses were also destroyed in the
rocket attack.
</P>
<P>
Afghan government forces in Kabul retaliated with artillery
fire but no casualties on the Taliban side were reported.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban troops have been stationed on the mountains south
of the Afghan capital since last October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report quoted some Taliban sources as saying
that the student militia had scored some victories on the
battlefields east of Kabul.  
</P>
</TEXT>
