<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chongqing, Bridge between China's East, West (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing has been an water
transportation and commercial hub in southwest China for at least
500 years.
</P>
<P>
Today, this most populous city in the country has emerged to be
the largest, most active economic center in the southwest, as well
as in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River Economic Zone.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese hold that Chongqing, which is at the junction
between the developed east China and the underdeveloped western
region, and between the Yangtze River area and the southwestern
economic zone, is playing the greatest-ever regional role in the
country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Over the past dozen years, the central government has shown
special care and has made various efforts to push forward the
economic progress of the inland industrial metropolis.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, Chongqing was declared the country's first city to
pilot comprehensive reforms and was granted provincial-level
economic power.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, Chongqing was listed among cities along the Yangtze
River to enjoy the same open policies as coastal open cities. Two
years later the State Council announced the Three Gorges Dam Area,
with Chongqing as its center, the Three Gorges Economic Open Zone.
</P>
<P>
Top state leaders, including President Jiang Zemin and Premier
Li Peng, have paid visits to Chongqing, encouraging it to play a
regional central role to boost the economy of the whole area.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has missed no opportunity to
strengthen regional economic cooperation and has invested heavily
in infrastructure. During 1991-95 period, its infrastructural
investment exceeded 30 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing now has three major railway lines, eight river ports,
and over 40 air routes to other parts of the country. The city's
water navigational link with Shanghai enables its shipping fleet
to reach the oceans, while its air transportation network can
transport passengers to any part of the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication sector has grown substantially in recent
few years, with a million telephone lines connected to everywhere
in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 08:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Increases Offsets 10 Percent of Jordanians' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A recent study by the NSCP regarding extra expenses resulting
from price increases, including bread price hikes, demonstrated
that the additional expenses various families have to be burdened
averages 32.2 dollars, according to today's Jordan Times, the
kingdom's sole English daily.
</P>
<P>
NSCP President Homhammad Obeidat said that the average income
of the surveyed families, with an average of seven members each,
was 175 dinars (about 225 dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said that some families who earn less than 175 dinars have
been badly affected and that such families pay up to 10 percent
of their income to cover the rise of bread price.
</P>
<P>
The government lifted the subsidies on bread last month, which
triggered the so-called "bread riots" in the southern part of the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
