<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Passes 1997 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean cabinet
adopted today a budget bill scaled at 87 billion U.S. dollars for
the next year, up 13.7 percent from that for this year.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which calls for a 13.5-percent increase in per capita
tax burden to 2,500 dollars, will be signed by President Kim
Young-sam and then submitted to the National Assembly for its
deliberation by October 2.
</P>
<P>
The general-account budget is set at 82.36 billion dollars and
the special-account budget at 4.64 billion, representing increases
of 12.8 percent and 33.9 percent respectively over those for this
year.
</P>
<P>
On the revenue side, tax revenue will rise 14.6 percent to
78.04 billion dollars, but non-tax revenues such as stock sales
proceeds will decrease 12.5 percent to 4.31 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 budget reflects the government's belt-tightening
measures stemming from a slowing economy and increased investment
in infrastructure expansion projects, according to Finance and
Economy Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's defense expenditures for the next year will be
raised by 12 percent to 17.34 billion dollars, the biggest raise
by the Kim Young-sam government since its inauguration in February
1993.
</P>
<P>
Spending for education will rise 17.6 percent to 22.64 billion
dollars and investment in rural restructuring programs increases
15.9 percent to 8.17 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Environment expenditures will be increased by 36.3 percent to
2.56 billion U.S. dollars, and research and development spending
will be raised by 27.3 percent to 3.91 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
