<HEADLINE> Western Politicians Criticized for Meeting Dalai Lama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A signed article released by
Xinhua today has criticized a number of politicians in the West
for regarding the Dalai Lama as a "distinguished guest" and
meeting with him.
</P>
<P>
The article by Li Rong said that since the beginning of this
year, the Dalai Lama has visited Australia, Japan, New Zealand and
the United States to preach his fallacy of "independence of
Tibet," in an attempt to internationalize the Tibet question.
</P>
<P>
"What he has done has laid bare his ugly face of seeking power
and wealth by betraying his motherland," it said.
</P>
<P>
For such a splittist who is bent on sabotaging China's
unification, however, some politicians in the West lauded him as a
"distinguished guest", met him and hosted private dinners in honor
of him.
</P>
<P>
Recently, an Australian politician went so far as to laud the
Dalai Lama as a "religious leader."
</P>
<P>
"What kind of person is the Dalai Lama?" the article asked.
</P>
<P>
It said that Dalai has been in exile and stuck to his
reactionary stand of betraying the motherland since an armed
rebellion in Tibet launched by him was crushed in 1959.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, instigated by some foreign forces,
Dalai has resorted to all kinds of activities to split China by
stirring up riots in Tibet and begging foreigners for support.
</P>
<P>
The article noted, "plenty of facts have demonstrated that
Dalai is the chieftain of the splittist clique attempting to seek
independence of Tibet, a chessman of the global anti-China forces
and the root for creating social disturbance in Tibet."
</P>
<P>
All far-sighted people all over the world have drawn a line of
distinction between themselves and Dalai, a conspirator who has
been engaged in activities to split China under the cloak of
religion.
</P>
<P>
But certain Australian politicians have not done so, it said.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, they stated repeatedly that they pursue
the 'one China' policy. On the other hand, they asserted that
meeting with the Dalai Lama does not mean that they support
independence of Tibet, adding that this is their concept of values.
</P>
<P>
Such a concept of values means one's deeds do not match one's
words," the article said, noting: "This is really absurd."
</P>
<P>
The reason some Australian politicians, with ulterior motives,
did the absurd thing of meeting with Dalai despite the Chinese
government's serious warning, is that they refuse to abandon their
intention of interfering in China's internal affairs, the article
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
