<HEADLINE> New Drug Detector to Be Used at Kuala Lumpur Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur
International Airport in Subang near here will be equipped with a
new device capable of detecting various drugs, according to a
senior official of the National Narcotics Agency (NNA) today.
</P>
<P>
The device -- Vapor Detector and Analyzer -- is very sensitive
in detecting drugs including Ecstasy and explosives hidden in
suitcases and this will enhance the authorities' ability to foil
smuggling attempts, NNA Director General Yaacob Mohamed Amin said.
</P>
<P>
The device is part of an American grant in combating drug
problems in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Yaacob was quoted by the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
as saying that the NNA was aware that the country was being used
as a transit point by traffickers to smuggle drugs from the Golden
Triangle to other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
He said recent arrests made by the authorities at the airport
confirmed this.
</P>
<P>
On September 15, two Singaporeans on their way to Jakarta were
held at the Kuala Lumpur International Airport while trying to get
away with 11,000 Ecstasy pills.
</P>
<P>
Yaacob said drug abuse was an international problem and
tremendous effort was being made by the Malaysian government to
tackle it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
