<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity Available in More Rural Areas in Xinjiang (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bagmahalla Village was lucky enough to be included in the
campaign, and since the beginning of this year, technical workers
have been constructing the necessary basic facilities. These
included the installation of 50 sets of household electricity
supply units, one central power supply system, as well as building
a ground satellite receiving station, and a power-driven water
intake mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Villagers became so excited on drinking clean water following
the availability of electricity in the village that they all
gathered together under bright electric lamps, singing and dancing
till the next day.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have selected another four similar backwater
villages after finishing the work in Bagmahalla. Like Bagmahalla,
the four poor areas will also say good-bye to the days without
electricity.
</P>
<P>
French experts working in the cooperation project say that
Xinjiang has rich solar energy resources and is an ideal area for
turning solar energy into electricity. Each year some 2,300 hours
to 3,500 hours of high-value sunshine can be harnessed each year.
</P>
<P>
Up to the end of last year, electricity had been available in
all counties of Xinjiang thanks to the help from the central
government, but some 500,000 households still can not use
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the Bagmahalla experience shows that
compared with building big power grids, using solar energy to
generate electricity can cut costs by two-thirds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electricity Available in More Rural Areas in Xinjiang (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Sunshine has brought a ray of
happiness for 70-year-old Niyaz Kaus, a farmer in northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the wonders of hi-tec solar energy, the farmer is now
able to leisurely watch TV in his own home.
</P>
<P>
Electricity - via the sun - has arrived in Bagmahalla village
in the Turpan Basin.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 200 households in the village have been supplied
with free TV sets, courtesy of local government departments.
</P>
<P>
And the village toasted the arrival of electricity by drinking
fresh clean water, again thanks to sun-generated power. They
danced all night long to say farewell to their 'dark age'
existence, illuminated only by kerosene lamps.
</P>
<P>
The transformation came about with the implementation of a
Sino-French cooperation project to use sunlight to generate
electricity.
</P>
<P>
Newly converted TV fan Niyaz said: "I like watching Mikamu -- a
sort of ballad popular among people of Uygur background --
programs most, and next comes general news broadcasts."
</P>
<P>
Bagmahalla used to be one of the remote poverty-stricken
villages in the Turpan Basin, where electricity was not available.
</P>
<P>
Until this summer the Uygur farmers of Bagmahalla used kerosene
at night for lighting, and young people had to ride long distances
in mule-driven carts to watch films or TV programs in neighboring
villages.
</P>
<P>
The French energy foundation signed an agreement to cooperate
with the Xinjiang Energy Institute at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, both sides are jointly building solar
energy-turned-electricity in villages within a time span of 26
months. They selected remote ethnic inhabited areas where no
electricity has ever been available, with the French side
providing technical and equipment aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Changes in Stance on Salman Rushdie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Ministry has
issued a statement, denying any change in its stance regarding the
death sentence on British author Salman Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
The statement, published in today's Persian daily Jumhuri
Islami, said that Iran's stance toward the Indian-born British
author of the Satanic Verses is the same as previously stated in
Iran's negotiations with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry issued the statement in a response to an
article in western media, which revealed that Iran and the EU had
reached 95 percent of an agreement on the Rushdie issue. The
article claimed that Iran would make a written guarantee not to
kill Rushdie in European countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the decree issued by the late
spiritual leader Imam Khomeini on Rushdie is "unchangeable."
</P>
<P>
"But as previously agreed upon, Iran would not send
commandos to execute the order," it said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that "what have appeared in some western media in the
past few days are nothing more than a ploy against the Islamic
Republic of Iran."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry called on Iranian people to be very
vigilant as regards what they read or see in the media.
</P>
<P>
On February 14, 1989, the late Iranian leader Ayatollah
Khomeini issued a religious edict, pronouncing a sentence of
death on Rushdie and his publishers in protest against the
publication of Rushdie's novel The Satanic Verses, and exhorting
all Moslems to carry out the sentence.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Rushdie issue has turned into a big
controversial problem that hinders the relations between Iran
and European countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Iranian authorities have given in to tremendous
pressures from the European Union after the death of Khomeini,
promising not to dispatch any commandos to kill Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati has pledged that Iran
would not send anyone to kill Rushdie. Similar assurances have
been given to European Union by President Hashemi Rafsanjani and
Parliament Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Donates New Trolley Buses to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China today handed over a
fleet of 10 trolley buses to the Nepali capital of Kathmandu under
an aid program to help upgrade the city's trolley transport
system.
</P>
<P>
The 10 new buses, worth about 800,000 US dollars, are expected
to significantly improve the service of the 13 kilometer long
trolley routes established in 1974 with 22 buses under a Chinese
assistance project.
</P>
<P>
The new buses, each with a full carrying capacity of 100
passengers, were handed over to the Nepal Transport Corporation at
a ceremony attended by Nepali Transport Minister Bijaya Gachhadar
and Chinese ambassador to Nepal Zhang Jiuhuan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Gachhadar said that as the air
pollution problem worsens in Kathmandu due to the rapid
urbanization, the trolley bus service has become a non-pollutive
alternative to relieve the ever increasing pressure of public
transport in the city.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed thanks to the Chinese government for its
cooperation in helping develop and improve the trolley system in
the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Nepal transport corporation, which has
operated the Kathmandu trolley system since its establishment 22
years ago, said that the trolley system has been providing
reliable and continuous service and is popular among the city
commuters.
</P>
<P>
About 425,000 commuters use the trolley service every month,
according to the officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
