<HEADLINE> Beijing to Expand Overseas Labor Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China's capital Beijing plans
to send thousands of experts and skilled people to other countries
as part of a 15 year plan to boost its share of overseas contracts.
</P>
<P>
The city has announced an expansion of its overseas labor
services and construction cooperation, with an increase of 10 to
15 percent annually, a top municipal official said.
</P>
<P>
He said by the year 2000, the total turnover of overseas labor
services is expected to reach up to 600 million US dollars, and by
1.4 billion US dollars by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
A number of effective measures are to be taken to achieve the
goal, said Yi Xiqun, director of the Beijing Municipal Foreign
Trade Commission. The most important is to extend overseas
contracts and labor services in accordance with international
standards.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Beijing had signed contracts for overseas
projects and labor services totaling 2.57 billion US dollar, with
a turnover of 1.13 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 doctors, scientists and engineers have been
sent to over 50 countries and regions around the world, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
A total 11 enterprises in the city have now been licensed to
enjoy the right to sign overseas contracts for labor services.
</P>
<P>
Among them, the Beijing Urban and Rural Construction Group Co
is the biggest, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city signed contracts for overseas cooperative
projects and labor services worth 780 million US dollars, earning
millions of dollars in profits for China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
