<HEADLINE> Asian Food Technology Show Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The third Asian Food
Processing and Packaging '96 (AFPP '96) incorporating Asian food
technology '96 Exhibition (AFT '96) Opened here today.
</P>
<P>
AFPP/AFT '96 is Malaysia's premier food processing-related
exhibition covering a comprehensive spectrum of food processing
and packaging equipment, machinery and technology.
</P>
<P>
Officiating the opening of the four-day show, Malaysian
Agriculture Minister Sulaiman Daud said efforts would need to be
directed at upgrading food processing technology; encouraging
higher automation; improving food quality, safety and health
standards as well as products design and packaging to ensure the
food industry remains competitive.
</P>
<P>
He said the growth of sophisticated consumers subsequently
translate into greater emphasis for product diversification, the
development of convenient food, upgrading of nutritive value and
food safety, and the development of special food for specialized
health needs.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian food market, he said it was already valued at
22 billion ringgit (about 8.63 billion US dollars) in 1995 and the
industry is projected to grow by 10 to 15 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
He said that by the year 2000, the food processing market of
the country alone is expected to be worth more than 10 billion
ringgit (about 4 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
As Malaysia's export of processed food products increases, with
growth from 812 million ringgit (about 318 million US dollars) in
1986 to 2.41 billion ringgit (about 945 million US dollars) in
1994, it will not only face increasing competition but also
barriers in the form of health regulations and other trade
challenges, he said.
</P>
<P>
To meet these challenges, he said entrepreneurs must strive for
higher standards of hygiene in processing, packaging, cold-storage
transportation and refrigeration through using sophisticated
processing techniques including those found in food biotechnology,
membrane technology, extrusion technology, ultra-high temperature
technology, ultra-high pressure technology and electro-heat
technology, etc.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition serves to boost the rapid growth of the food
processing and packaging industry in Malaysia and in the region
and aims to provide an excellent opportunity for both Malaysian
and foreign investors to undertake business collaboration,
organizers at the show said.
</P>
<P>
Over 150 exhibitors representing some 20 countries and regions
are displaying their products and technology at the biennial
event.  
</P>
</TEXT>
