<HEADLINE> Beijing Praises Reporters Who Help Fight Copyright Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China's State Copyright
Administration today rewarded 50 reporters who have helped fight
copyright piracy over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The reporters work for Xinhua News Agency, "The People's
Daily", China Central Television, and many other news
organizations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
"Mass media is playing a major role in promoting people's
awareness of copyright protection," said Yu Youxian, director of
the administration.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese media has published tens of thousands
of stories to demonstrate the significance of copyright protection
and spread information in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Many people reported copyright cases to the authorities after
reading newspapers, according to Shen Rengan, deputy director of
the administration. He added that it was unusual for a country to
mobilize all its public sectors, including the media, to engage in
the fight against copyright piracy.
</P>
<P>
Yu Youxian explained that the improvement of people's legal
sense by making use of the media has become a basic guarantee to
implement the copyright law.
</P>
<P>
The prize-winning stories themselves are a showcase that China
has achieved great progress in protecting copyright, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He cited some articles, including one describing how farmers
become familiar with the copyright law, one about the Walt
Disney's case in Beijing, and another on copyright protection in a
fast food restaurant.
</P>
<P>
Some reporters lashed the US for its unfair charge that China
violated foreign copyrights. One journalist even told a story
about a senior Chinese copyright official whose works were pirated
in the US without authorization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
