<HEADLINE> Atlantis Undocks from Mir for Ride Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. space shuttle
Atlantis undocked from Russian space station Mir today, ending the
five-day joint operations and picking up woman astronaut Shannon
Lucid back for the ride home.
</P>
<P>
The two spacecraft separated slowly while flying over European
mountain region at 9:33 p.m. EDT, right on time as scheduled.
About two hours later, commander Bill Readdy will fire Atlantis'
engines to move quickly from Mir for the final time until Atlantis
returns to the Russian station next January for another docking.
</P>
<P>
The nine astronauts and cosmonauts finished final transfer
activities and verified the inventory lists of materials Sunday
night. More than one ton of water was transferred from Atlantis
to Mir, along with logistical supplies, food and scientific
hardware.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before 6 a.m. EDT today, the crew gathered in the Core
Module of the Russian space station for a formal good-bye.
</P>
<P>
Lucid gave her colleagues aboard Mir a farewell embrace and
then floated into shuttle Atlantis, the hatch between the two
spacecraft closed behind her at about 8 a.m. EDT, concluding five
days of joint operations.
</P>
<P>
"I'm really happy and I also feel just a little sad," said
Lucid, who holds the space endurance record for a woman and an
American. The 53-year-old biochemist spent seven more weeks in
space than planned because Atlantis' trip was delayed by its
booster rockets problem and two hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis' landing remains scheduled for Kennedy Space Center on
Thursday at about 8:12 a.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
