<HEADLINE> Anticipatory Bail Granted to Son of Bangladeshi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The high court of Bangladesh
has granted a two-month anticipatory bail to former prime minister
Khaleda Zia's son, Tareq Rahman, and some others charged with
different corruption cases, court sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
A division bench of the high court Monday also issued a ruling
directing the government to show cause within four weeks as to why
the petitioners should not be enlarged on an anticipatory bail.
</P>
<P>
The ruling of the court came after three day's of hearing of
the petition beginning on Saturday seeking anticipatory bail to
avoid arrest and police harassment.
</P>
<P>
The court granted similar anticipatory bail to Khaleda Zia's
brother Iskander Ali and three former ministers of her cabinet who
were implicated in separate corruption cases lodged by the
Anti-corruption Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The bureau on September 16 charged that the Dandy Dying
company, owned by Tareq Rahman and Iskander Ali, had obtained a
loan of about four million US dollars from a state-owned bank
illegally by abusing the power of the then prime minister Khaleda
Zia.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyer Moudud Ahmed argued that the corruption case
lodged by the government was in a bid to tarnish the image of the
incumbent opposition leader Khaleda Zia, who was defeated in the
June 12 parliamentary elections. 
</P>
