<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Banks Closed in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nine more Bulgarian banks were
closed and will be given special supervision and management by the
central bank, the management council of the People's Bank of
Bulgaria, announced today.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time this year for Bulgaria to declare the
possible bankruptcy of commercial banks. Bulgaria declared the
closure of two banks last May.
</P>
<P>
Special supervision and management means that the central bank
will send supervisory officials to those banks, stop their
businesses and clear up their debts. Once the central bank decides
that they have lost their paying ability, it will declare to the
courts their applications of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also said today that the yearly interest rate
and the monthly rate of the bank would rise respectively to 300
percent and 25 percent. It also suggested that commercial banks
raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank explained that this measure was designed to
minimize the effect of inflation on people's lives.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Prime Minister Zhan Videnov hailed the central bank's
decision. He said on state television tonight that these timely
and necessary measures would help stabilize the country's
financial systems.
</P>
<P>
Georgi Petkov, director of the central bank's Lev Business
Department, told reporters that the purpose of raising interest
rates was to withdraw currency from circulation. The high rates
might indicate the coming of serious inflation, said Petkov.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's inflation rate has surpassed, since the beginning of
this year, the current yearly interest rate of 108 percent of the
People's Bank. And the rate of exchange between the Lev and
U.S. dollars has changed from 70 to 1 in the middle of this year
to 240 to 1 now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Air Force Denies Drug-Plant Involvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian air force today
denied that it had helped place the heroin found on the
presidential plane Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing could be more illusory and unreal" than these
allegations, Air Force Commander General Hernando Gil said today.
</P>
<P>
The air force considered the finding of 3.7 kilograms of heroin
in the presidential aircraft "deplorable," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the anonymous phone call that led authorities to discover
the drug in the nose of plane, Gil said that the call was received
after the inspection of the craft by air force security had begun.
</P>
<P>
Taking the notification seriously, the process was expedited
with the support of intelligence teams and anti-narcotic dogs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The heroin would have been located anyway, even if there had
not been such a call, he added.
</P>
<P>
The heroin was found in the plane in which President Ernesto
Samper was due to fly to New York to attend the 51st U.N. General
Assembly session. 
