<HEADLINE> Conventions Help Parties Raise Near Record Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Republican and
Democratic parties had one of the most lucrative fund-raising
periods in August partly because of their presidential nominating
conventions.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party again topped the Democrats by taking in 23
million dollars in August. It spent almost 4.4 million dollars to
produce and air TV ads for Bob Dole, who was pressed against the
legal limit on a presidential primary spending.
</P>
<P>
The pre-convention aid chipped away at the 74 million dollars
that Dole is allowed to spend on his fall presidential campaign,
which officially began when he became presidential nominee on
August 14 in San Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
Dole and President Bill Clinton, who was renominated last month
in Chicago, each received 62 million dollars in taxpayer funding
for the fall campaigns. In addition, each is allowed 12 million
dollars in direct aid from his political party.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats, boosted by their convention and contributions
raised at cross-country birthday bashes for President Clinton,
took in about 15 million dollars, a party spokesman estimated
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Democrats' best fund-raising month to date was June, at 16
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
When the last quarter ended in June, the Republican committee
led the Democrats in fund-raising, 144 million dollars to 122
million dollars, for the election cycle that began January 1, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Republican National Committee reported details of its
fund-raising to the Federal Election Commission Monday. The
Democratic National Committee, which files quarterly reports, will
not file its financial information until October 15.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party's take includes about 6.6 million dollars
in unrestricted "soft money" donations from corporations and
wealthy patrons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
