<HEADLINE> World Bank's MIGA Posts Record Growth in Fiscal 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The outstanding portfolio
of the Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency (MIGA) has more
than doubled in the past two years, the agency announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
The MIGA, a member of the World Bank Group, said its investment
guarantee increased from 1 billion U.S. dollars at the end of the
1994 fiscal year to about 2.3 billion dollars in coverage in
fiscal 1996, which ended on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal 1996 marked a record growth in the MIGA's 7-year-old
investment guarantee business. The agency issued 68 investment
guarantee contracts for 862 million dollars in new coverage, as
compared with 54 contracts for 672 million dollars in fiscal 1995.
</P>
<P>
MIGA-insured projects also exceeded the fiscal 1995 total in
the amount of foreign investment facilitated, which is 6.6 billion
dollars as compared with 2.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1996, the MIGA assisted private firms from 17
different countries in making investments in 27 host developing
countries. MIGA insurance in fiscal 1996 covered investments in a
broad range of countries and sectors.
</P>
<P>
Investment guarantees were issued for the first time in Kuwait,
Kyrgyztan, Mali, Nepal and Papua New Guinea. It also provides
technical assistance to help developing countries and transitional
economies in their efforts to attract foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The MIGA's membership increased to 134 countries with the
addition of six countries in the year while signatory countries to
the MIGA Convention totaled 155. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
