<HEADLINE> Kesri Out to Strengthen India's Congress Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Newly appointed provisional
president of the Congress Party Sitaram Kesri told reporters last
night soon after his appointment, "I will try everything possible
to strengthen the party."
</P>
<P>
Senior Congress leader Sitaram Kesri was chosen by the Congress
Working Committee (CWC), the highest policy-making body of the
party, to be the provisional president of the Congress to succeed
P.V. Narasimha Rao.
</P>
<P>
Rao resigned soon after a Delhi court issued an order Saturday
summoning him as the co-accused in the 100,000 US dollar cheating
case to appear in person before it on September 30.
</P>
<P>
Never discarding the Gandhi cap ever since he joined the
Congress, Kesri belonged to a rare tribe of congressmen who never
left the party during its numerous splits since 1969.
</P>
<P>
Born in Dinapore in Bihar state in eastern India 80 years ago,
he plunged into the freedom movement when he was barely 13 years
old. He was imprisoned by the British first in 1930 and six times
more later in the struggle against the British rule over the
country.
</P>
<P>
Working tirelessly for the party, Kesri's first major break
came in 1973 when he became president of the Bihar parliamentary
Congress committee and remained at the post till 1977.
</P>
<P>
During the past two decades, he has been the treasurer of the
Congress since 1977.
</P>
<P>
His ministerial debut came in 1980 when the late Indira Gandhi
made him minister of parliamentary affairs. Two years later he was
made the minister of state for shipping and transport. He was
minister for welfare in the Rao's cabinet since 1991.  
</P>
</TEXT>
