<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asia to Work Out Strategy Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Doctors from South Asian
countries gathered here to discuss the current situation of AIDS
and tuberculosis (TB) in the region and to work out a common plan
of action to fight TB associated AIDS co-epidemic.
</P>
<P>
A SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation)
consultative meeting on TB and AIDS opened here Monday to
formulate policies and strategies to control the deadly diseases
in a coordinated way.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
According to participants, the World Health Organization (WHO)
puts the number of HIV-positive cases in South Asia at 1.5 million
while in the meantime the region sees more than three million new
TB cases every year.
</P>
<P>
The situation is getting worse as more cases of TB associated
HIV infection are reported, they warned.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the co-epidemic of TB and AIDS will increase
sharply in TB cases, which claim about 1 million lives in the
South Asian region every year according to WHO estimates.
</P>
<P>
About 60 to 80 percent of AIDS patients suffer from TB too, and
the TB associated AIDS has become the cause of over half the
AIDS-related deaths, they told the meeting.
</P>
<P>
They argued that preventative steps are the best measure to
combat TB and AIDS in the poverty-stricken SAARC region, urging
member states to make common efforts to overcome the problem.
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting, organized by the SAARC Tuberculosis
Center (STC) in Kathmandu, is attended by 15 TB and AIDS experts
from Nepal, Bangladesh, India, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Economy Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China is to introduce
policies to encourage enterprises to save resources and gain
maximum utilization in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The new economy-drive policies will comprise of many facets
including taxation, finance and credit, the Beijing-based
"Economic Information News" reported.
</P>
<P>
New policies on taxation will include exemption and reduction
of taxes on developing energy-saving products and technology, low
tariffs on importing equipment for the comprehensive use of
resources, and the exemption and reduction of value-added taxes on
the development of new sources of energy.
</P>
<P>
Heavy taxes will be imposed on the manufacture of products
which consume high levels of energy and cause serious pollution,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In finance, enterprises carrying out technological
transformation in the comprehensive use of resources and
developing renewable energy resources will enjoy a discount in
bank interest rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
