<HEADLINE> Clinton Expects U.S.-Russian Ties to Develop Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton said today that he is confident the U.S.-Russian relations
will develop smoothly, despite the health problem of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the remarks at the white House when signing the
U.S. defense spending authorization bill for the 1997 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government has "come a long way in developing
constitutional mechanisms of authority," and the United States has
maintained "regular contact" with other top Russian officials
including Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, he said.
