<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Petrochemical Project in Qaidam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China is to build a 4.3
billion yuan petrochemical project in the Qaidam Basin, northwest
China's Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Zhou Yongkang, deputy general manager of
the China Oil and Gas Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Zhou explained that during the current Ninth Five-Year Plan
Period (1996-2000), the country will carry out large-scale
exploitation of the natural gas reserves in the Qaidam Basin. The
construction of the project is aimed at promoting the economic
development of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
</P>
<P>
He added that according to an initial plan, the project will
have a designed annual production capacity of 120,000 tons of
polyvinyl chloride, 100,000 tons of caustic soda, 200,000 tons of
synthetic ammonia and 350,000 tons of urea.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that the project had already passed assessment and
appraisal from China International Consultancy Company, and his
corporation has been negotiating over the investment possibility
with US company, Amoco Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Qaidam Basin has an area of 240,000 square kilometers,
equivalent to the size of Great Britain, and it is also one of
China's four major basins.
</P>
<P>
China has discovered 22 oilfields in the Qaidam Basin after
more than four decades of prospecting. Of the 22 oilfields, six
fields, with combined natural gas reserves of 54.1 billion cubic
meters, boast sound conditions for full-scale development.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the installation of a 189 km pipeline
from Sebei Oilfield to Golmud City, also located in the basin,
which will form part of the new petrochemical project, has just
been finished. A 16,000-kilowattt power station using natural gas
as fuel has also been built.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
