<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dazhai Becoming Popular Tourism Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Dazhai, a village in Xiyang
County in north China's Shanxi Province, became nationally known
in the 1960s as a "pace-setter" in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Now it has become a popular destination for domestic and
overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, during the first eight months
of this year, more than 60,000 Chinese and overseas tourists
visited the village. It is expected that the number of tourists to
Dazhai will reach 100,000 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s Dazhai was mostly ignored by outsiders. Today
however, there has been a revival, and visitors can find pavilions
and a long corridor scattered amongst the greenery of nearby Hutou
Hill, with the yellow roof reflecting the bright sunlight.
</P>
<P>
The emergence of Dazhai Village Comprehensive Building of
Industry and Trade, the Sheep Wool Sweater Factory, a joint
venture between Dazhai Village and an overseas investor, a cement
plant and other agricultural and breeding facilities shows the
tremendous changes the country's reform and open-up drive has
brought to the mountainous village.
</P>
<P>
The officials attributed the boom in tourism to the opening in
June of the Taiyuan-Jiuguan Expressway, and is now also linked to
Beijing-Tianjin and Beijing-Shijiazhuang expressways.
</P>
<P>
Many people visit the village to receive education in
patriotism, said the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Foreign Investment to Drop in 1996/97 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's foreign
investment inflow in 1996 and 1997 would slow down, growing by a
mere 15 percent a year compared with the 25 percent in 1995, while
the inflation rate would remain above eight percent in the same
period, the Bureau of Statistics warned.
</P>
<P>
In its report released here Monday, the bureau cited
inconsistent micro-economic policies as the main culprit of the
sluggish foreign investment in addition to high bank interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment approvals, according to the Investment
Coordinating Board, declined in value by 2.7 percent to 21 billion
US dollars between January and July 15 this year from 27.2 billion
in the same period of last year. Meanwhile, the value of domestic
investment approvals rose 127 percent to 70.6 trillion rupiah (one
dollar equals 2,320 rupiah) from 31 trillion rupiah.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, foreign investment approvals rose 68 percent to 39.9
billion US dollars from 23.7 billion in 1994, while domestic
investment approvals increased 30 percent to 69.9 trillion rupiah
from 53.3 trillion.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Statistics said that the slower foreign
investment growth would result in a decline in the aggregate
growth of gross domestic capital to 7.67 percent in 1996 and 7.91
percent in 1997, compared with the 8.4 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
It also expected the country's inflation rate to reach 8.5
percent this calendar year and 8.9 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The bureau attributed the high estimates to continued increases
in demand for consumer products.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government had planned to keep the inflation
rate at 5 percent per annum in the current five year development
period ending in 1999. The target has yet to be achieved, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bureau of Statistics, government policies to
fight inflation through fiscal and monetary measures have not been
effective due to growth in short-term foreign funds through
domestic equity and money markets.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
