<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A dissolution of the Thai
parliament may be inevitable if coalition parties cannot agree on
a new prime minister to succeed Banharn Silpa-archa, a coalition
party Prachakorn Thai (Thai Citizen) leader Samak Sundaravej said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Banharn announced last Saturday he will resign within seven
days and choose a successor from his coalition.
</P>
<P>
If the six coalition parties cannot reach agreement before
today's cabinet meeting, they will have to try again afterwards,
Samak was quoted today by local daily the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Once Banharn Silpa-archa announced his successor, a government
should take shape without problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prospect of a dissolution, he said, depended on how
Banharn's Chart Thai (Thai Nation) assessed political conditions.
Anyone wanting a dissolution must make Chart Thai angry.
</P>
<P>
According to another report today, Banharn has proposed Pongpol
Adireksarn, minister of the prime minister's office, as Chart
Thai's choice to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Banharn made it clear that he would propose to a
Chart Thai meeting this afternoon that it back Pongpol Adireksarn.
</P>
