<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Overseas Income to Hit 7 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The central bank of the
Philippines projected that the country's overseas remittances
would hit a record-high 7 billion US dollars this year, an
increase of 42 percent from last year's 4.9 billion, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Babriel Singson, governor of the central bank, told a press
conference Monday that this healthy influx of foreign exchange
from the export of services will help bring down the country's
ballooning trade deficit which reached 7.1 billion dollars in the
first seven months of the year.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, this is seen to lead to an even healthier buildup
of the country's foreign exchange reserves. By the end of August,
the central bank's gross international reserves had reached 11.43
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the prediction was based on the growth of overseas
income in the first six months this year. He added that
remittances during this period had already amounted to 3.48
billion dollars, or a hefty 57-percent increase from the year-ago
level of 2.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
"The uptick is expected to continue in the second half of the
year, particularly during the fourth quarter, when remittances
traditionally shoot up as the Christmas season nears," Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the overseas income will continue to play an important
role in the development of the national economy because it will
take some time for merchandise exports to outpace imports.
</P>
<P>
However, economists reiterated that the sustainable development
of the country's economy should not be hinged on the "volatile"
income from overseas workers. They asked the government to
concentrate on promoting merchandise exports and foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
According to the local press, there are now 4 million Filipinos
working in more than 120 countries or regions. About 60 percent of
the overseas workers are female and most of them are housemaids or
entertainers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
