<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Positives Up Among Colombian Heterosexuals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of people in
Colombia infected with the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV),
which causes AIDS, reached 16,331 in August, says a report by
Colombia's Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 9,331 were people with no symptoms, which meant that
they had not so far developed AIDS, while 6,981 had.
</P>
<P>
HIV cases among heterosexuals had increased, while those among
homosexuals and bisexuals had decreased.
</P>
<P>
Until August of this year, 1,518 became infected from
heterosexual contacts. The number of homosexual transmissions was
1,087, while the bisexual cases numbered 550.
</P>
<P>
This demonstrated that homosexuals were changing their sexual
behavior, while heterosexuals were not yet aware of the danger of
the disease, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Bogota, the nation's capital, recorded the largest number of
new HIV positives with 716, followed by Antioquia with 330, Valle
del Cauca 323, Atlantico 175, Santander 166, Choco 40 and Huila 39.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health established a phone line on August 20
to offer free information on sexually transmitted diseases and
AIDS. People in Colombia living outside Bogota can make a
toll-free call to the city.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3,044 Colombians have died of AIDS, since the
disease was first recorded in 1983 in the city of Cartagena de
Indias. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
