<HEADLINE> Guatemala's Peace Process to Enter Final Stage in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The coordinator of
Guatemala's Peace Commission, Gustavo Porras, announced today that
the government and the guerrillas will enter the final stage of
the peace process in October.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Guatemala City said the delegations from the
government and the Revolutionary National Unity of Guatemala will
debate on the "operative" topics on October 3-5 in Mexico City,
which comprise the final part of the negotiations agenda.
</P>
<P>
The operative topics include the reentry of combatants into
civil life, amnesty, cease-fire and demobilization.
</P>
<P>
On September 19, the Guatemalan government and the guerrillas
signed an agreement that paved the way to a final accord to end
the 36-year civil war in this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
It was the last of the six agreements on social, economic and
political issues between the civilian government and the
guerrillas since the peace process began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, aiming to strengthen the civil power and the
role of the army in a democratic society, calls for a 33-percent
reduction of the armed forces and allows the defense minister to
be a civilian.
</P>
<P>
Other agreements include human rights, the relocation of
displaced people, the identity and rights of the indigenous
peoples, socioeconomic issues and agricultural reforms.
</P>
<P>
A final accord is expected to be signed later this year to end
the civil war which has left 175,000 people dead, 45,000 missing
and 1 million displaced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
