<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Americans to View Last Lunar Eclipse of Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguans and many other
Central and South Americans will be able to observe the last total
lunar eclipse of the century this Thursday, astronomer Claudio
Gutierrez said today.
</P>
<P>
The next full eclipse that people of the region would be able
to see would not happen until January 20, 2000, said the expert.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's event will begin one-and-a-half-hours after sunset
and the eclipse will last for at least one hour.
</P>
<P>
Only people in Central and South America will be able to view
the total eclipse. It will be almost invisible in Europe and only
slightly visible in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Gutierrez said that four to seven lunar eclipses took place
each year, but many were partial. The last full eclipse visible
to the area occurred in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
