<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Foreign Debt Up 64 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's foreign debt has
increased by 64 percent over the past 10 years, said financial
sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Treasury and Public Credit said
that, by June this year, the country's total foreign debt had
reached 165.5 billion U.S. dollars, equivalent to 56.3 percent of
the gross domestic product (GDP) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The refinancing process, which the government implemented last
year, had helped curb foreign indebtedness and achieved a 4.6
billion dollar decrease from 1995 when it reached its highest
level.
</P>
<P>
Mexico currently pays an annual interest rate of 8.25 percent,
similar to what it paid in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Mexico entered a phase of excessive debt as foreign
debt increased for the federal government, the development bank,
the Banco de Mexico and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, international liabilities went up from 142.2 billion
dollars to 170.2 billion dollars, because of new loans from the
U.S. Treasury Department and the International Monetary Fund for
helping curb the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, tax authorities made prepayments on the
government debt, which only decreased from 100.9 billion dollars
to 98.5 billion dollars in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
