<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi Sets High Goals for Harnessing Loess Plateau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province
plans to harness 50 percent of its soil erosion area by the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to years of efforts to harness the Loess Plateau, Shanxi
has so far contained 51 million mu (3.06 million hectares), or 32
percent of its total eroded area.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, located near the middle reaches of the Yellow River,
occupies a large part of the Loess Plateau. Soil erosion area
accounts for 70 percent of its total 156,000 square kilometer of
ground.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s, the annual amount of sand washed into the
Yellow River stood at 366 million tons -- one-fourth of the
river's total.
</P>
<P>
A large-scale campaign to harness the Loess Plateau first began
in the 1980s. Over the following several years, 350,000 local
rural households participated in the drive.
</P>
<P>
By planting grass, trees and crops, and building dams and
terraced farmland, the residents revived hundreds of thousands of
barren gullies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the central government and the Shanxi provincial
government also worked to prevent the spread of erosion in the
Loess Plateau.
</P>
<P>
The central government has invested 75 million yuan to tackle
erosion of the banks of the Sanchuan River and Yongding River, two
large rivers on the plateau. Eroded areas which have been
controlled there account for 40 percent of the total drainage area
of the two rivers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 150 million yuan has been used in harnessing the
upper reaches of the Fenhe River, the second largest tributary of
the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Erosion-harnessing projects were carried out on an area of 1.95
million mu (117,000 hectares) there. In the region, grain output
increased by 50 percent, farmers' income rose two-fold, and the
volume of sand which washed into reservoirs was reduced by 49
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
