<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets Yugoslav Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China appreciates
Yugoslavia's policy of peace and wishes to see peaceful
coexistence between the countries in the regions of former
Yugoslavia, said Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen here today.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Yugoslav Foreign Minister Milan
Milutinovic here this morning, Qian, who is also foreign minister,
said that some positive progress has been made in Yugoslavia and
in its related regions.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is here attending the 51st Session of the General
Assembly of the United Nations, said that there has been some
improvement in the environment.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia plays an important role in maintaining peace and
stability in the former Yugoslav regions," Qian said, adding that
China appreciates the peace policy of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Milutinovic, who met Qian for the first time since he became
foreign minister, briefed his Chinese counterpart on the latest
peace process. With the ending of Bosnia's post-war elections, the
international community should lift sanctions against Yugoslavia
in all sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister said that China is against the
practice of applying sanctions against a country lightly.
</P>
<P>
"Now that Bosnia's election is being held according to
schedule, we hope the international community will keep its
promise and lift sanctions against Yugoslavia," Qian said, adding
that China also hopes that countries in the region will be
friendly to each other and establish normal relations among them.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers expressed their satisfaction for the
development of bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
