<HEADLINE> NATO to Send Follow-up Peace-Keeping Forces to Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker
Ruehe confirmed here today that NATO will send follow-up
peace-keeping forces to Bosnia-Herzegovina after the present
Implementation Force (IFOR) finishes its mission on December 20.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said for this purpose defense ministers of 16 NATO
members will meet in Bergen, Norway, on September 25 and 26, to
discuss tasks of the follow-up forces, and entrust military
personnels to draw up operation plans for them.
</P>
<P>
The follow-up forces of 20,000 to 25,000 will mainly work to
maintain stability among Bosnia political forces, prevent new
fightings, and explain, supervise and implement the Dayton peace
agreement singed last year.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, however, that the forces' new tasks will wait to
be finally approved by the United Nations and NATO in November.
</P>
<P>
Germany will dispatch 2,000 to 3,000 men to participate in the
peace process in the same manner as other NATO partners, he
disclosed. Up till now, its main task in Bosnia has been
providing logistics services.
</P>
<P>
The coming NATO defense ministers meeting, he added, will
signal that NATO will officially begin its eastward expansion next
year, and at a summit later, name the first group of candidates,
possibly including Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, for
NATO membership.
</P>
<P>
NATO will also reach an agreement with Russia on a charter to
serve as foundation for their "brand new relations of
partnership," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
