<HEADLINE> Heavy Fightings Reported on Zairean-Rwandan Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Heavy exchanges of artillery,
rocket and machine-gun fires were reported from Sunday night to
Monday morning on the Zairean-Rwandan border between Bukavu,
eastern Zaire, and Cyangugu, southwest Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Bukavu has been shelled by bombs "from the Rwandan territory
and the Zairean army has counterattacked," according to National
Radio of Zaire monitored here.
</P>
<P>
"The information has been confirmed by the Ministry of
Interior," said the radio.
</P>
<P>
Fighting was first reported by Radio Agatashya, a Swiss-funded
independent radio in the Great Lake region of central Africa.
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross in Kinshasa, capital of Zaire, also
confirmed that intensified fightings took place Sunday night, but
was unable to say which side opened fire first.
</P>
<P>
It said that the situation was "totally normal" in Bukavu this
morning, with all the markets open and children going to school.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Zaire accused Rwanda and Burundi of
"fomenting troubles" in the region of Uvira south to Bukavu, but
met rejection from both of them.
</P>
<P>
Zairean troops launched at the beginning of the month a
large-scale hunting of Rwandan and Burundian Tutsi armed elements
in the hills of Uvira near the Burundian border.
</P>
<P>
About one million Rwandan Hutu refugees have been living in
refugee camps in eastern Zaire, after they fled Rwanda following a
genocide committed by Hutu army and militias against Tutsis and
Hutu moderates in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
