<HEADLINE> Low GDP Growth Registered in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's annual Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) growth averaged less than one percent
during the first five years of market reforms ended last year,
while total debt soared to over 4.3 billion U.S. Dollars, the
United Nations said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an analysis of African countries economic situation,
U.N.Secretary-General Boutros Boutros Ghali said economic
performance in Zimbabwe was lower than that recorded in
Mozambique, whose GDP growth averaged 3.08 percent, Swaziland
(2.51 percent), Tanzania (1.24 percent) and Botswana (3.45
percent).
</P>
<P>
The highest growth, of 4.33 percent was registered by Uganda,
which the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund last
year praised for its commitment to harsh market reforms to
reverse years of stagnation.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth in Zimbabwe between 1991 and 1995 was mainly
affected by two droughts in 1991/92 and 1994/95, which reversed
the marginal gains made when the southern African country
embarked on western-backed market reforms at the beginning of
1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, Zimbabwe's population growth
between 1991 and 1995 averaged 2.36 percent, while the total debt
rose from 3.43 billion U.S.Dollars in 1991 to 4.4 billion
U.S.Dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Life expectancy, probably reflecting the magnitude of the AIDS
pandemic, declined from 60 years in 1991 to 54 years in 1994, so
did the infant mortality rate per 1,000 live births, which fell
from 61 in 1991 to 57 in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
