<HEADLINE> Rwandan Defence Minister Arrives in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Defence Minister Paul
Kagame arrived here today to find out how Zimbabwe can assist in
bolstering the country's return to peace in the aftermath of the
1994 civil war and genocide.
</P>
<P>
Kagame, who is also Rwandan Vice-President, said the genocide
had seen the destruction of human life and infrastructure and
Rwanda could draw lessons from Zimbabwe on how to cement
reconciliation among its different sections of the population and
achieve economic development.
</P>
<P>
''We are trying to create sufficient stability and carry on
those processes (reconciliation and economic development) and
Zimbabwe can be very helpful in terms of enabliing us to bring
about that stability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Kagame's visit comes after the
United Nations lifted restrictions on the sale or supply of arms
or related material to the Rwandan government with effect from
September 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The restrictions were put in 1994 when the government then in
power engahged in genocide and massacres which left up to a
million Tutsis and moderate Hutus dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
