<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Monitors to Resume Meeting in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A five-nation committee
monitoring a cease-fire between Lebanon and Israel is to resume
its meeting in a south Lebanese border town Tuesday to discuss
complaints lodged by Lebanon and the Jewish state against each
other.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called by Lebanon to consider two complaints
it filed to the committee accusing Israel of violating the
cease-fire by shelling southern Lebanon's villages last Thursday
and deporting two Lebanese families from a border strip occupied
by the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel also complained to the committee that guerrillas of
Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, fired on its
forces from three civilian-inhabited villages in the area that
day.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour session at Naqura Sunday, the cease-fire
monitoring committee, which groups the United States, France,
Israel, Lebanon and Syria, adjourned the meeting until Tuesday
because of the Jewish holy day of Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
It was the forth meeting of the cease-fire monitoring
committee, but the first at Lebanon's request. The previous
three meetings were called by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up under a cease-fire understanding
brokered by the U.S. between Lebanon and Israel, which put an
end to a 17-day Israeli blitz in April against Hezbollah, and
which is aimed at protecting civilians on both sides from any
military activities.
</P>
<P>
Reliable official sources close to the Lebanese delegates in
the committee said that the Sunday meeting was limited to
handling the first Lebanese complaint pertaining to the Israeli
bombardment at southern Lebanese villages and wounding civilians
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli delegates admitted the truth in the Lebanese
accusation, but claimed that the shelling took place because
Lebanese guerrillas opened fire from houses in the villages
during a fighting with the Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Tensions escalated in south Lebanon since the Thursday clash
in which two Israeli soldiers were killed and at least eight
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
The casualties brought to 20 the number of Israeli soldiers
killed by Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon this year.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation for the guerrilla attack, Israeli jets and
artillery blasted southern Lebanese villages, wounding a woman
and a child. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Team Ends Visit to Bakassi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Fact-Finding
Team ended its visit to the disputed Bakassi Peninsula on Sunday, with
an appeal to both Nigeria and Cameroun to exercise restrain, the local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
During its three-day stay in Cameroun and five-day stay in Nigeria,
the four-member team met with officials of both countries and heard
their views of points on the Bakassi disputes. The team also went to
disputed area for on-spot investigations.
</P>
<P>
Team Head Omar Halim said the visit was to ensure the
maintenance of peace and security in the disputed area, before
the international court of justice in the Hague gives its
judgement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The dispatch of the team was suggested by UN Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali. Reports say the team will return to Cameroun
for further consultation upon ending its Nigerian tour, but Nigerian
sources are not available for confirmation at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Cameroun have been clashing over the oil-rich
Bakassi Peninsula since 1994, with the latest conflicts
occurring last April. enditem

