<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Down Sharply on Wall Street's Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Europe's leading stock markets
all ended down sharply today, undermined by worries about monetary
policy on both sides of the Atlantic and by an early 50-point fall
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Losses on Wall Street weighed on an already volatile London
market ahead of the outcome of monetary policy meetings both in
the U.S. and in Britain, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Markets were poised for a quarter point base rate rise in the
U.S., but few economists expected any changes at the latest
meeting between Kenneth Clarke, the Chancellor, and the governor
of the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
British shares closed 44.4 points down, or 1.12 percent lower
today after hitting an intraday peak of 3,994.1 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt also finished lower, 19.06 points
down on the DAX-30 share index, in cautious trading ahead of
Tuesday's U.S. Federal Open Markets Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Dealers also cited profit-taking after record gains Friday as
another driving force for the market's losses.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks ended down 12.37 points on the CAC-40
share index along with London and Frankfurt. Bearish world markets
and fears of more French public sector strikes weighed on shares
prices there, traders said.
</P>
<P>
London's Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 leading
British shares closed 44.4 points lower at 3,919.7. The Frankfurt
DAX-30 index ended 19.06 down at 2,627.04. The Paris CAC-30 share
index finished down 12.37 at 2,067.09. 
</P>
</TEXT>
