<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Uganda To Strenthen Bilateral Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Uganda
have agreed on the need to further strengthen and deepen
bilateral relations between the two countries, especially in the
field of undertaking joint projects.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique issued here today at the end of Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni's four-day visit to Tanzania, the two
sides also resolved to expand cooperation in training of
personnel and exchange of information in forestry, biogas,
environment, oil and mineral exploitation.
</P>
<P>
The Joint communique signed by Museveni and Tanzanian
President Benjamin Mkapa stressed the necessity to improve road
transportation between the two countries to enhance business
transactions.
</P>
<P>
It called for the revitalization of the joint permanent
commission of cooperation and urged responsible ministers of the
two countries to meet as soon as possible to re-assess and review
the objectives of the commission.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state also underscored regional economic
cooperation and integration as the key to overcoming some of the
regional problems and as a way of building up the envisaged
African economic committee.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held extensive discussions on the problems
affecting the region, especially the situation in Burundi and
condemned the military coup in that country.
</P>
<P>
They re-affirmed their commitment to the decisions made by the
Arusha regional summit held on July 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
