<HEADLINE> Southern African Countries Urged to Develop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The southern African
countries have been called upon to develop agriculture to meet
food requirements of the people.
</P>
<P>
The minister for Agriculture and Cooperatives of Tanzania, Paul
Kimiti, made the call today when he opened the 5th southern African
countries meeting on farming systems research and extension in Arusha,
northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Kimiti said that further agricultural development would be attained
when food production exceed population growth, currently standing at
about three percnt in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said more agricultural production could be the answer for
the population pressure, which had negative effects to the
environment as it could cause soil erosion, loss of biodiversity and
groundwater pollution becasue of the excessive use of agro-chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Kimiti told participants from nine southern African
countries that commodity research in the region was appreciable, but
the rate of adoption of innovations had not reached the expected
level.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Arusha, the three-day conference draws
researchers and agricultural extension officers from Botswana, Kenya,
Malawi, Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe
and Brazil. enditem

