<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Condemns Aggressive Separatism at UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Irakli Menagarishvili,
foreign minister of Georgia, today strongly condemned "aggressive
separatism," which has become the main cause threatening
international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the general debate of the 51st session of the U.N.
General Assembly, Menagarishvili said that aggressive separatism,
though not a new phenomenon, has only comparatively recently come
into the focus of the world community, due to its global nature
and its destructive impact on international security.
</P>
<P>
"No matter what the fundamental underlying reasons for the
emergency of separatist movements, their nature, scale and
location, they have one thing in common: under the banner of
`self-determination of suppressed people,' regimes are created on
the ideological basis of terrorism," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.N. Charter and international law have
clearly determined that the right of self-determination, going as
far as the creation of independent states, is provided to peoples
under colonial suppression.
</P>
<P>
"But it is unacceptable when this principle is misused by
national minorities, or nations small in number, who have
historically constituted a single society with other nations,
within the framework of sovereign states, which today are members
of the United Nations," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
International law does not allow the encroachment of such
peoples and ethnic minorities onto the territorial integrity and
political unity of democratic states, respecting human rights and
giving these groups of people the possibility to preserve their
national character, cultural development, up to and including the
creation of political institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"That's why, when we speak of the necessity of struggling
against aggressive separatism, we have in mind a national minority,
or small nation, using weapons or foreign military support, to
break away a part of historic territory of a state within which it
exists," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aggressive separatism uses ethnic cleansing as the main tool of
vengeance against other nations and ethnic groups, which have
resulted in millions of refugees and displaced persons, he said.
For example, 300,000 Georgian citizens were expelled from the
territory of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
On preventing and overcoming separatist tendencies, he put
forward the following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- to define separatism in terms of international law as a
phenomenon so as to identify and categorize aggressive separatism
in international legal documents;
</P>
<P>
-- to introduce and enforce economic measures, including
economic sanctions, against aggressive separatism;
</P>
<P>
-- to take measures of military-political character such as
imposing an embargo on supplies of arms to the regions where
separatism takes aggressive forms; and
</P>
<P>
-- to punish those who have committed crimes against humanity
through international tribunal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
