<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen Meets 51st General Assembly President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier
Qian Qichen assured the president of the current General Assembly
of the United Nations that China will give its support to his work
and wishes he will succeed at his post.
</P>
<P>
On the first day attending the General Assembly's sessions
today, Qian, also the minister of foreign affairs, met with Razali
Ismail, the newly elected U.N. president, at the U.N. headquarters
in New York. Qian expressed his belief that Razali, who is
concurrently Malaysia's permanent representative to the U.N.,
will promote a smooth development of different tasks of the U.N.
during his tenure.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the recent official visit by Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir bin Mohamad to China, Qian said that there exists
fine cooperation between China and Malaysia. China supports
Razali's work, he said.
</P>
<P>
Razali said that China is the sole developing country among the
five permanent members of the Security Council. Therefore, he
said, it will best understand the aspirations of developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
China has made important contributions to the United Nations,
he said, and the U.N.'s future development could hardly be carried
out without the involvement of China.
</P>
<P>
Qian noted that the U.N. has the heavy tasks of maintaining
peace and promoting development. China will work together with
other developing countries to this end, he added.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's permanent representative to the U.N., was
present at the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
