<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK PM Delighted by Anti-Terror Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major said today he was "absolutely delighted" by the success of
the raids in London earlier this morning which foiled the bombing
plans of the Irish Republican Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
It "put in their proper context professions of peaceful
intentions by Sinn Fein's leaders and speculation about a renewed
IRA cease-fire," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
A very large quantity of explosives was recovered, as well as
firearms and bomb-making equipment, Scotland Yard said.
</P>
<P>
"The operation has undoubtedly frustrated a serious imminent
IRA terrorist attack on the British mainland involving the
deployment of a large vehicle bomb likely to have caused grave
loss of life and massive disruption," it added.
</P>
<P>
During the raids, an Irish guerilla suspect was killed. The
dead man was wounded in a shoot-out as police officers arrested
him and five other suspects. Police said he died in hospital
shortly afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The IRA has planted a number of bombs in Britain since calling
off a 17-month-long cease-fire in February, citing British
intransigence over the progress of peace efforts in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein expressed regrets that somebody was killed in the
series of dawn anti-terrorist raids. Its leader Gerry Adams said
he presumed the IRA had been the focus of the operation.
</P>
<P>
He warned a vacancy in the peace process and said there was an
"absolute lack of confidence" in Britain's commitment to peace.
</P>
<P>
However, John Major reaffirmed in his statement, "The British
government remains fully committed to the Belfast negotiations
aimed at a comprehensive political settlement in Northern
Ireland."
</P>
<P>
"Northern Ireland's future will be settled by democratic,
peaceful discussion, not by violence or threats of violence. It is
time Sinn Fein and the IRA learned that lesson once and for all,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
