<HEADLINE> U.S.To Resume Commerical Food Aid to Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is likely
to resume its commercial food aid to Mozambique in 1997,
said representaive of the U.S.Internatioanl Aid Agency (USAID) in
Maputo, George Wachtenheim.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.commercial food aid to Mozambique was suspended in
February this year after 1800 tons of food aid provided by the
U.S. was stolen at Port Maputo at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The US decision to resume its food assistance came after the
Mozambican police detained nine suspects involving in the theft
and the Mozambican government paid an indemnity of 247,000
U.S.Dollars to the U.S. this month.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. food aid to Mozambique in 1997 will be a small
amount and it will reach the proper amount in 1998, George
Wachtenheim said in an interview with the Mozambican Information
Agency today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
