<HEADLINE> US Set to Allow Ukraine to Join MTCR: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
is set to allow Ukraine to join an international missile control
accord while building missiles banned by the pact, The Washington
Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. policy is being drawn up in preparation for a
plenary session of the 28-nation Missile Technology Control Regime
(MTCR) member nations in Edinburgh, Scotland, in early October,
the paper quoted Clinton administration officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that if
the new U.S. policy was approved at the meeting, Ukraine would
have the right under the MTCR to obtain advanced missile
technology and assistance from the United States and other
members.
</P>
<P>
The MTCR restricts exports of missiles with ranges greater than
186 miles and warheads heavier than 1,100 pounds.
</P>
<P>
But it also contains provisions that facilitate the sharing of
missile technology among members of the pact.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian officials have reportedly indicated that Kiev wants
to joint the MTCR but still be allowed to acquire several types of
missiles currently barred under the treaty, including
ground-launched ballistic missiles with ranges up to 310 miles
and air-launched cruise missiles with ranges up to 372 miles.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and foreign critics say that the new U.S. policy on
admitting new members to the MTCR would severely undermine efforts
to halt the spread of missiles around the world by promoting other
nations to join the pact as a way to acquire long-range missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
