<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Loses One Billion US Dollars Annually due </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tsetse flies infest over 10
million square kilometers in Africa, an area which if cleared of
the menence could support an additional 120 million cattle,
generating one billion U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed today by Kenyan Permanent Secretary in the
Ministry of Technical Training and Applied Technology Wamatu
Njoroge.
</P>
<P>
In his speech read during the official opening of agriculture
research co-ordination meeting here, the permanent
secretary said 60 percent of Kenya's rangelands, about 25 percent
of the total landmass, cannot support livestock because of tsetse
infestation.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Wamatu Njoroge said about 50 million
people in Africa are at risk of acquiring sleeping disease adding
that surveillance in many known endemic areas is difficult.
</P>
<P>
He said the impact of both human and livestock sleeping
disease on the African continent has led to the under-exploitation of
resources in rangelands, and that the disease forces the
concentration of livestock in limited grazing areas, resulting in
overgrazing and land degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
