<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Minister on Price Hike of Petroleum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Trade and Industry Kassahun Ayela said today the increase in the
price of petroleum products will not have significant
repercussion on the economic status of the consumer since the
resulting effect will be cushioned by the better performance of
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The remark was made by the minister after the Ethiopian
government announced an increase of prices of petroleum products
effecting from last Sunday. For example, one liter of petrol
sells at 2.33 Birr (0.36 U.S.Dollar) from September 21, 1996, as
against 2 Birr before.
</P>
<P>
Kassahun was quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency as saying
that several economic indicators were considered and much caution
has been taken before the issuance of the price regulation to
make the effect minimal.
</P>
<P>
He said the regulation was necessitated by the increase in the
price of crude oil, from 17 Dollars per barrel two and half years
ago to the current level of 21 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
The measure taken by the government is part of the move toward
the ending of the subsidization system which is contrary to the
principles of the free market economy, the Ethiopian minister
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
