<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perot Files Suit Over Presidential Debates Exclusion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Reform Party candidate
Ross Perot filed a suit today seeking a court order to bar
presidential debates from going forward without him.
</P>
<P>
"We're charging that the whole Commission on Presidential
Debates constitutes an illegal contribution to the (Republican and
Democratic) parties," said law professor Jamin Raskin, one of
Perot's lawyers, outside the federal courthouse.
</P>
<P>
Rankin is associate dean of the American University Law School
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two 90-minute presidential debates are for October 6 and
16.
</P>
<P>
Today's filing is scheduled to go to U.S. District Judge Thomas
Hogan, and asks for a temporary restraining order and eventual
permanent injunction to include Perot in the debates.
</P>
<P>
Outside the U.S. courthouse today, Perot's national coordinator
Russell Verney told reporters and a group of Reform Party
supporters that Democrat Clinton and Republican Dole both bear
responsibility for Perot's exclusion -- Clinton for allowing his
negotiators to agree on debates without the third-party candidate,
and Dole for actively opposing Perot's inclusion.
</P>
<P>
"There is no more fundamental exercise of free speech in this
country than the right to vote for the candidate of your choice,"
Verney said. According to polls, at least 73 percent of the U.S.
public wants Perot included in the debates, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Democratic and Republican parties should not be permitted
to consolidate their monopoly on the political process by closing
off the presidential debates" to Perot and Choate, said the
26-page lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
"Declaring the election essentially over for all candidates but
two before a single debate takes place will only deepen the
nation's cynicism about government," it added.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit asked the federal court to direct the debate
commission or the Federal Election Commission "to either extend an
invitation to Perot and his running mate to participate in the
debates, or to cancel any debates staged and sponsored by the
CPD."
</P>
<P>
In today's filing against the Federal Election Commission and
the debate commission, Perot's lawyers argued that the commission
did not follow FEC rules when selecting debate participants.
</P>
<P>
"The FEC has unlawfully delegated control over debate selection
criteria to the five Democratic and five Republican members of the
(commission), who, in turn, have forsworn their obligation to
apply only objective candidate selection criteria," the filing
said.
</P>
<P>
Perot captured 19 percent of the votes in the 1992 presidential
election, but is registering only in single digits in current
political polling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
