<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Finds More Users Taking Direct Route to Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A survey of home computer
users has found for the first time, more people are gaining access
to the Internet through direct Internet services than through
commercial on-line services, the New York Times said today.
</P>
<P>
The findings of the semiannual Homefront survey by Odyssey Inc.
of San Francisco said that 48 percent of all households connected
to the Internet used an Internet Service provider like Netcom and
AT&AMP;T Worldnet, compared with 35 percent who used a commercial
on-line service like America Online and Compuserve.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, just six months ago 54 percent of
households with Internet access used a commercial on-line service,
as against 30 percent for the Internet providers.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the service providers, who typically offer home computer
users access to the Internet but little else, the commercial
on-line services create a self-contained world of services and
features available only to paying members.
</P>
<P>
The survey data also indicated that 14 percent of all
households in the United States now have access to the Internet or
to an on-line service. Over all, 36 percent of all households have
a personal computer of some sort, which means that on-line
households are still a minority even among PC households.
</P>
<P>
Among households that have an on-line connection, electronic
mail emerged in the survey as the most popular application,
followed by research, news and information gathering. The least
popular applications were home banking, on-line shopping and
making hotel and airline reservations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
