<HEADLINE> French Attorney Blames British Airways for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- An attorney general for the
Appeal Court of Paris today blamed British Airways for a 1990
hostage crisis in Kuwait, which was caused by the landing of an
airliner of the company in Kuwait City hours after the Iraqi
invasion.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Georgette Benas said that British Airways (BA)
no doubt "committed a fault" by landing the BA 149 passenger
plane with some 65 passengers on board in Kuwait City on August 1,
1990, but she said that the fault "isn't inexcusable."
</P>
<P>
All the passengers, including some Frenchmen, became "guests"
of President Saddam Hussein and served as "human shields" for
three months during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
She said that the action of taking the passengers hostage by
Iraqi troops was not "previsible" and this action resulted from
"a brutally degraded situation in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The Paris Appeal Court will decide on November 12 whether to
support the lawsuit against BA by some former French hostages#,who
are asking for compensation for the psychological and physical
hardships during their detention by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Attorney Benas also said that the Warsaw Convention on
guaranteeing the security of ground and maritime passengers should
be extended to air travel.
</P>
<P>
She said that BA should be responsible for the security of its
passengers during the flight and during "all operations of
embarking and disembarking of passengers", and protect them
throughout the time when they were under its guide, such as by
evacuating them from the plane and sending them to a safe hotel.
</P>
<P>
Some of the former hostages suspect that the BA landed the
passenger plane in Kuwait in order to drop 30 British secret
agents in Kuwait on spy missions after the Iraqi invasion.
</P>
<P>
Gilbert Parleani and Dominique Menard, two lawyers for the
former French hostages, said that the fault committed by BA was
"extremely serious and inexcusable" because it landed innocent
civilians on a land of war engaging "the third largest army of
the world."
</P>
<P>
They said that "a bunch of elements" led one to think that
the reason for BA not to change its route to land in nearby
Bahrain was that it wanted to drop 30 British agents in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Some passengers said that the plane took off two hours late
from London, before some 30 young men "whose manners were
different from those of other passengers" embarked the plane.
</P>
<P>
Some British newspapers and a book published in London also
claimed that London wanted to send spies into Kuwait "by one
blow" after Saddam Hussein invaded the sheikhdom.
</P>
<P>
Fernand Garnault, attorney for BA, said that the commander of
the crew of BA 149 was reassured several times before and during
the flight that his plane could land without problem.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that there were Iraqi soldiers on the (Kuwaiti)
frontier, but difficulties had existed for a long time between
Iraq and Kuwait," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the hostages could be saved "by someone else than
British Airways" and that moreover, the passengers were entitled
to compensations from the Funds of Guarantee of Victims of Acts of
Terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
