<HEADLINE> Angola Urges Int'l Community to Aid Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Minister of
External Relations Venancio de Moura today called for a new
"Marshall Plan" before the end of this century to help Africa
through its social and economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the general debate of the 51st session of the U.N.
General Assembly, de Moura said that the crisis that is currently
afflicting the global economy is mostly structural in nature, and
results from the lack of consistency, lack of coordination and
adoption of macro economic policies incompatible with the growth
needs of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
"Of great concern is the realization that the current growth
rate of some of our countries is often negative, compelling whole
populations to lead lives of starvation and extreme poverty," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfair to know that at the threshold of the third
millennium, we still have 800 million malnourished people across
the world," he added.
</P>
<P>
On Africa, he said that it is the continent most lacking in
capital and technologies and, as a result, its population growth
far exceeds its food production capacity.
</P>
<P>
He considered that one of the basic keys to the economic and
social development lies in the expansion and re-orientation of
economic cooperation for development.
</P>
<P>
"We must map out as soon as possible a global developmental
strategy that will contribute to the solution of the problems now
affecting the survival of our economies," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the debt issue, he said that for the lesser developed
nations, the sole viable solution is total forgiveness for the
debt and a massive effort in the area of international cooperation
for development of partnerships.
</P>
<P>
He called on strengthening south-south cooperation and regional
economic integration, which will pave the way for the
establishment of more equitable new international orders and free
from measures of protectionism.
</P>
<P>
De Moura also expressed supports of the General Assembly
resolutions appealing for the lifting of the economic blockade and
in favor of the Cuban people, who suffer under the negative of
effects of that measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
