<HEADLINE> U.S., Turkey Agree to Curb Saddam's Influence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
assured by Turkey that it supports U.S. policy on Iraq and would
not encourage Saddam Hussein to extend his influence in northern
Iraq, a State Department spokesman said on Monday in New York.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Burns said Secretary of State Warren Christopher and
Turkish Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller, both of whom are in New
York to attend the United Nations General Assembly, held 40-minute
talks, in which Christopher was satisfied that Turkey assured him
not to collaborate with Saddam.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of today's meeting, Turkey and the United States
firmly agree that Saddam's influence in northern Iraq should be
minimized," said Burns.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times on Saturday published an interview with
Ciller, who was quoted by the newspaper as saying that her
government was talking with Saddam about establishing enough
control in northern Iraq to chase out Turkish Kurds waging a
separatist guerrilla war against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Burns said Ciller's earlier reported remarks "caused some
anxiety in Washington", since the Clinton administration is
striving to minimize Saddam's influence in the region and has
resorted to military action to hem him in further.
</P>
<P>
Ciller told reporters before meeting with Christopher that she
had been misunderstood by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We are worried about the security of our borders," she said.
"We want to stop the influx of refugees through our borders. But
we cannot ask Saddam to do that for us", because Turkey respects
U.N. resolutions concerning Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We have lived up to all that was asked from us by the United
States," she added.
</P>
<P>
Ciller told Christopher during their talks that Turkey has
established a "security zone" in northern Iraq to block
cross-border incursions by the Kurdish Kurds who are fighting a
separatist war from bases in norther Iraq and increasing their
attacks on Turkish government forces.
</P>
<P>
Christopher told Ciller that the Clinton administration did not
object to the "security zone" so long as it was not permanent.
</P>
<P>
"He said the United States will continue to support the Turkish
security zone, that our understanding is that it would be
temporary in duration, and Mrs. Ciller concurred in that," Burns
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
