<HEADLINE> Mortuary Workers Convicted of Corruption by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Three mortuary workers were
given suspended sentences of three to six months in jail by a
court in Pontoise, 50 kilometers north of Paris, for "passive
corruption" in leading the families of the dead to a funeral
director's company which paid them commissions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Claude Glanzman, manager of the New Agglomeration
Funeral Director's Company of Cergy-Pontoise, was convicted of
"active corruption" and was given a suspended sentence of six
months in jail.
</P>
<P>
The court also gave one franc (0.2 U.S. dollars) of
compensation to a rivaling funeral director's company -- the
Funeral Director's Company of Cergy-Pontoise, which claimed that
it had been inflicted with more than one million francs (200,000
U.S. dollars) of loss by the unfair competition from its rival.
</P>
<P>
Dominique Douet, Ernest Margain and Yannick Peufly, who worked
in the mortuary of the central hospital of Pontoise, said that
they only received tips sometimes from the funeral director's
company for doing extra works.
</P>
<P>
A dozen families of the dead said that the three men
"effectively guided them to choose which organizer of funeral
ceremonies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
