<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Direct Investment Soars with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The business
globalization is accelerating at a dramatic pace, indicated by a
surge of foreign direct investment, according to the 1996 World
Investment Report published today by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign direct investment into developed and developing
countries surged by 40 percent in 1995, to reach 315 billion U.S.
dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
About 100 billion U.S. dollars went into developing countries,
a gain of 15 percent on 1994. "China alone took in more than 38
billion U.S. dollars," it says.
</P>
<P>
"China played a key role in attracting foreign investment among
developing countries," said Georg Kell, an official with the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) which
prepared the annual report.
</P>
<P>
Kell said the figure was 4 billion U.S. dollars more than that
in 1994. "For this year, we expect a slight decrease, a temporary
adjustment due to some new policies introduced in China," he said.
However, he added, China would undoubtedly retain its very
important position as a host country for foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment into Asia continued to boom, he said.
Asia absorbed about two-thirds of all foreign direct investment
inflows into developing countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. retained its absolute lead both in terms of inflows and
outflows, according to the report. In 1995, about 60 billion U.S.
dollars were invested in the U.S. by foreign transnational
companies and the U.S. was the home country of nearly 100 billion-
U.S.-dollar outflows of foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The report says foreign direct investment between Western
Europe and the United States set new records and was dominated by
mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
However, growth of investment into Asia may well outpace growth
into Europe in the future, the U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment inflows are still highly
concentrated, the report says. The smallest 100 recipient
countries received only 1 percent of total investment. The top 10
largest recipient countries accounted for 68 percent of the 315
billion U.S. dollars of inflows.
</P>
<P>
Latin America attracted about 27 percent of all foreign direct
investment to developing countries, with two-thirds of this
accounted for by just four countries.
</P>
<P>
In Africa over the past couple of years, annual investment
flows to the continent have been around 5 billion U.S. dollars
only, according to the report.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
