<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Deficit Declines in First 11 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. federal deficit,
which totaled 144 billion dollars in the first 11 months, declined
by 15.9 percent from the same period of fiscal 1995, U.S. Treasury
Department announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the government deficit of fiscal year
of 1996 ending on September 30 probably will be the smallest
annual imbalance in seven years.
</P>
<P>
It said that the deficit probably will end the year less than
144 billion dollars, because September usually winds up with a
surplus from quarterly income tax payments.
</P>
<P>
It would be the fourth straight annual decline after the
deficit peaked at a record 290.4 billion dollars in 1992 and
probably the lowest since 152.5 billion in fiscal 1989.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration forecast in July that the deficit
for the fiscal year would be 116.8 billion dollars, down from its
original forecast of 160.6 billion last spring.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government deficit in the first 11 months of last
fiscal year was 171.1 billion dollars and it was down to 163.9
billion at the end of fiscal 1995.
</P>
<P>
The last U.S. budget balance was in fiscal year of 1969 with a
surplus of 3.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Even with the size of the annual deficits of U.S. government
going down in the past four years, the total national debt has
increased to 5.1 trillion dollars now. The national debt in the
U.S. includes all the annual deficits since the country was
founded plus borrowings from government trust funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
