<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Attacked for Suspending Cattle Slaughter Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
been criticized for unilaterally suspending its cattle slaughter
program and urged to stick to its agreement with the EU in a bid
to eradicate the BSE or mad cow disease, according to press
reports from Killarney, Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during the three-day informal meeting of
EU agriculture ministers in the southern Irish town Killarney, EU
Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler said that "the beef crisis
is the biggest crisis we ever had in the European Union."
</P>
<P>
The EU agriculture ministers, deeply concerned over Britain's
decision to suspend the cattle slaughter program, have been trying
to persuade Britain to stick to its agreement with the EU to wipe
out the mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
The British government last Wednesday decided to put on hold
the slaughter of the 147,000 cattle most at risk of BSE in view of
the so-called new scientific findings that suggest the mad cow
disease would be over by the year 2001 without the planned
slaughter.
</P>
<P>
Fischler said this afternoon that "if the British do not
implement the cull, then it is clearly a breach of the Florence
agreement" reached in July by EU leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Every step taken in the wrong direction does not help to
restore confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU Agriculture Commissioner noted that there would be
formal discussion of Britain's attitude at the talks on Tuesday
when all EU ministers sit down together to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
"We need clear proposals and clear signals to the farmers and
to the consumers and that must be the discussion tomorrow," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg said that
Britain would work with its EU partners to implement the Florence
agreement, but he made no reference to his govenment's decision to
suspend the cattle slaughter program.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed the global ban on British beef products exports
on March 27 when the British government admitted that there were
possible links between mad cow disease and its human equivalent
Creutzfeldt Jacob Disease.
</P>
<P>
EU leaders agreed at the Florence Summit in June to gradually
lift the ban on British beef exports on the condition that Britain
should implement a series of tough measures, including the
slaughter of those cattle most at risk from the mad cow disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Official Appeals for Ratification of Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- An EU (European Union)
official today urged EU member nations and African, Caribbean and
Pacific (ACP) countries to speed up the process of ratification of
the revised Lome-IV convention.
</P>
<P>
Joao de Deus Pinheiro, EU commissioner in charge of relations
with ACP group members, made the appeal Monday at an ACP-EU
round-table conference held in Luxembourg, according to a press
release issued here today.
</P>
<P>
"The ratification only took place in two EU member nations and
16 ACP countries," the commissioner said at the conference.
</P>
<P>
He asked the participants in the conference to play their due
roles to step up the process of the ratification in their nations
of origin and thus make the convention go into effect. The
convention includes the 8th European Development Funds (EDF).
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said, "More than ever, I am convinced that we
will have the credibility of our partnership."
</P>
<P>
In order to make the convention go into effect and ACP
countries benefit from the 8th EDF, the convention should be
ratified by at least two-thirds of the 70 ACP countries and all
the EU member nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
