<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs U.S. 1997 Defense Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton today signed the U.S. defense spending authorization bill
for the next fiscal year beginning on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The bill, providing a total of 265.6 billion U.S. dollars for
the Pentagon, is 11 billion U.S. dollars more than Clinton
requested.
</P>
<P>
While providing billions more for military research and the
purchase of new weapons than the Pentagon sought, the legislation
also gives a three percent pay increases for American military
personnel and the 4.6 percent increase in the allowance for
off-base living quarters.
</P>
<P>
"This legislation will increase the security of our country and
our families," Clinton declared at a special ceremony at the White
House. "This bill will allow our armed forces to remain the best
trained, best prepared fighting force on earth."
</P>
<P>
The authorization carries forth the U.S. Defense Department's
modernization programs by funding crucial weapons systems,such as
the F-22 fighters, the Comanche helicopters and the V-22 Osprey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
