<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFOR Seizes Weapons from Bosnian Muslim Returnees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The multinational peace
Implementation Force (IFOR) seized weapons from Muslims who
returned to the village of Jusici near Zvornik in the northern
part of Bosnian Serb territory.
</P>
<P>
IFOR spokesman Maj. Simon Haselock said in Sarajevo on Monday
that more than a dozen pieces of weaponry banned under the Dayton
peace accords had been confiscated from Muslims who began
returning to the village on Friday, according to Tanjug news
agency.
</P>
<P>
Another IFOR officer said about 100 Muslims had come to the
village, most of whom wanted to return home, but some with arms.
</P>
<P>
The armed men were suspected to be soldiers in civilian clothes
sent by the Muslim army, IFOR officials said.
</P>
<P>
IFOR troops are patrolling the village and monitoring
developments from nearby hills.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bosnian Serb Interior Minister Dragan Kijac said
Monday Serb authorities had asked the Muslims to leave Jusici and
Serb police would take control of the village.
</P>
<P>
IFOR spokesman Maj. Brett Boudreau said refugees could return
home only where it was safe, and that return to sensitive border
areas had to be gradual, with the help of international refugee
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
