<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR: 646,000 Refugees Housed in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A UNHCR official said here
Monday there are 646,066 refugees or displaced persons living in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Mission chief of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) in Belgrade, Margaret O'keeffe, told a press conference
that this was the official results of the registration of refugees
performed in Yugoslavia between April 15 and June 30 of this year.
</P>
<P>
The registration figures showed that more than 60 percent of
the total refugees had decided in favor of integrating themselves
into local communities in Yugoslavia, while 23 percent were either
"undecided," "uncertain" or had "no answer."
</P>
<P>
This means that Yugoslavia, which is comprised of Serbia and
Montenegro, with its enfeebled economy and exhausted households,
should absorb nearly half a million homeless, which was
"unthinkable," O'keeffe said.
</P>
<P>
This was why, she added, the UNHCR would go on assisting these
people and would also have to appeal on the international
community, agencies and donors to extend a broad-based financial
support to the integration of as many refugees as this.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR held that the question of the property of Serbs
expelled from Croatia should be resolved in the same way as that
of the property of refugees from Bosnia, because Croatia did sign
the Dayton agreement and the provisions of the accords should
therefore be applied to Croatia too.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Serbia's commissioner for refugees Bratislava
Morina told the same press conference that the recent
normalization of relations between Yugoslavia and Croatia and the
successful elections in Bosnia would encourage the return of
refugees and the resolution of the question of their legal
property and status.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum was being drafted on the voluntary return of
refugees to the Bosnian Serb entity Republika Srpska from Serbia,
she added.
</P>
<P>
During the three-and-half-year war in Bosnia, more than 2
million people had become refugees or displaced persons. About
600,000 fled to other countries outside the former Yugoslav region
and more than 600,000 in Yugoslavia. So far, only hundreds of
refugees have returned to Bosnia from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
