<DOCNO> XIE19960924.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qicheng Meets EU Troika Foreign Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qicheng Monday urged the European Union to
take more active steps to support China's efforts in entering the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
He made this remark during his meeting with his counterparts of
the European Union Troika here in New York.
</P>
<P>
Qian pointed out that in recent years the overall relationship
between China and EU is developing in a good direction.
</P>
<P>
He said China values the important role the EU and its members
are playing in the international affairs and wishes to develop
friendly and cooperative relationship with them.
</P>
<P>
On economic and trade relations, Qian said there is great
potential for development since the two sides are economically
complementary.
</P>
<P>
He said China will continue the process of opening up to the
outside world and liberalizing its trade practices.
</P>
<P>
He called upon the EU countries to take more positive steps in
eliminating protective trade barriers against Chinese products and
to take positive and concrete measures on the questions of China's
entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring, the current EU president,
told Qian that EU is determined in pursuing the long-term policy
of developing strategic relationship with China.
</P>
<P>
Noting the dialogue between China and EU has already had a good
beginning, Dick said that the EU is willing to continue such a
dialogue so as to enhance understanding and reduce differences.
</P>
<P>
Spring told Qian that the EU supports China's entry into the
World Trade Organization, hoping the question can be solved on an
equal and just base.
</P>
<P>
On the human rights issue, Qian reaffirmed China's consistent
policy that is to carry out dialogues with other countries on the
basis of equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
China believes that dialogues and confrontation cannot be mixed
together. If any country wishes to seek dialogues (with China), it
should discard the stance of confrontation, he added.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the European Union, Hans Van Mierlo expressed his
gratitude for the flexibility and constructive spirit China had
demonstrated in the negotiations for settling the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). He said China had made important
contribution to the successful adoption of the treaty earlier this
months.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier said that China had been actively
involved in the CTBT negotiations, holding that it would be the
first step taken toward the final target of a comprehensive ban
and complete destruction of nuclear weapons. He said the
international community should continue its efforts in this
regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
