<HEADLINE> Kasparov Records First Win in World Olympiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Gary Kasparov recorded his
first win on Monday to pace Russia for a 3.5-0.5 victory over
Czech Republic in the World Chess Olympiad in Yerevan, Armenia.
</P>
<P>
Russia kept its lead with 21 points as the Olympiad went half
way through its 14-round competitions.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov, the top player in the chess world, defeated Zbynek
Hracek, a Czech grand master.
</P>
<P>
Spain beat Britain 3:1 to break away from a three-member run
for the second place, while five teams of China, Hungary,
Bulgaria, Estonia and Uzbekistan tied for third place with 18
points each.
</P>
<P>
Two women players who lead men's teams lost their games
respectively, with Judit Polgar defeated by Bogdan Lalic of
Croatia and Pia Cramling by Joel Lautier of France.
</P>
<P>
British top seed Nigel Short was defeated by Alexei Shirov of
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ye Jiangchuan, coach of former world champion Xie Jun,
drew with American champion Alex Yermolinsky.
</P>
