<DATE_TIME> 1996-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Environment Better in Huangguoshu Waterfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The once-barren environment
surrounding Asia's biggest waterfall has been transformed into a
rich forest area.
</P>
<P>
Huangguoshu Waterfall in southwest China's Guizhou Province
attracts large numbers of domestic and overseas tourists every
year.
</P>
<P>
The waterfall, 81 meters wide and 69 meters high, has long been
the trump card in the province's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The region around the waterfall is karst, which makes it
difficult to grow trees and grassland, large areas of mountains in
the region were barren a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
So to protect the rich tourism resource, the region's tourist
bureau planted 520,000 trees and turned a total of 26,000 square
meter areas into grass lands.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has also signed 30-year-long contracts to rent large
areas of land on the upper reaches of the waterfall to farmers for
tree-planting.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the bureau's effort, the forest coverage rate in
the region has increased from three percent to 13 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
